<HEADLINE> Britain Sends Group to Liberia After Workers Abducted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, Aug 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain said on Thursday it was
sending a group of officials to Liberia to help the local
government to obtain the release of a group of Western workers
abducted there.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Office Minister Geoffrey Hoon said in a statement that
he had asked the British ambassador in Ivory Coast, a neighbour
country to Liberia, to go immediately to Liberian capital Monrovia
with a small team "to make direct contact with the Liberian
government, and to offer any advice and assistance they need".
</P>
<P>
Hoon said Britain had already been in contact with Liberian
government officials and "they agree that the safety of those who
have been abducted is of paramount importance.
</P>
<P>
"The Liberian government have made it clear that they wish to
see the incident resolved peacefully by negotiation," Hoon said.
</P>
<P>
"We look to the Liberian government to ensure the safe release
of all hostages as soon as possible," said the foreign office
minister.
</P>
<P>
The aid workers, including four Britons, a Norwegian and an
Italian, were abducted by an armed gang in Liberia on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
