<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lukashenko: Russian Government Change Won't Affect Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Belarussian President Alexander
Lukashenko expressed confidence Thursday that the government
change in Russia will make no impact on the two country's union.
</P>
<P>
"The union is a sacred objective aimed at the future. Therefore
it's impossible to slow it down," Lukashenko said in Gomel,
Belarus, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said attempts to draw out the integration process might
instead make "the unification process more radical."
</P>
<P>
In response to a draft of the union treaty taken from Moscow to
Minsk, he said, Belarus "proposed a more radical unification
option," envisioning such posts as union president,
vice-president, parliament and government.
</P>
<P>
"Russia honestly and sincerely said that it cannot accept this
proposal. In effect, the Russian draft will be adopted," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said both former Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin and
Vladimir Putin, his replacement, had worked on the draft treaty.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, Stepashin's stepping down and Putin's appointment
does not mean that we have stopped in the unification process,"
Lukashenko said.
</P>
<P>
"The process of creating a union continues slowly, the way it
did previously," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
