<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican President Calls on Youths to Fight AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano Thursday called on the youth in the country to fight the
AIDS scourge.
</P>
<P>
He made the call at a rally marking the World Youths Day here
in the capital, saying AIDS has posed a great threat to the youth
and further to the development of the country.
</P>
<P>
The rally, which drew over 1,000 attendants, is presided by the
National Youth Council with the help of the Mozambican government
and the United Nations Population Fund.
</P>
<P>
According to the president, there are 700 people getting
infected with the AIDS virus daily in his country. Among AIDS
patients in Mozambique, 42 percent are youths aged between 15 to
29.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Mozambique's Deputy Health Minister Abdul Razak
said the southern African country will launch an intensive
campaign against AIDS with the support of the United Nations so as
to control the ever increasing infection rate.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the infection rate of AIDS in Mozambique is between
10 to 15 percent, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
