<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgrade Says Anti-Yugoslav War Is Not Over DPA357PAB251I12TEQL03:2603:261174 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A senior Yugoslav
diplomat said here Thursday that the end of NATO's military
aggression "does not mean the end of war at all" against the
Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
Vladislav Jovanovic, charge d'affaires of the Yugoslav Mission
to the United Nations, told a press conference here that the peace
does not arrive in his country "because after the end of the
military aggression, NATO, headed by the U.S. Government,
continues the aggression against Yugoslavia by other means."
</P>
<P>
"The economic war is continuing, propaganda war is spreading
out, (and) underground war, subversive action is underway," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Jovanovic, who is former Yugoslav foreign minister, made the
statement when presenting a book entitled "NATO Crimes in
Yugoslavia -- Documentary Evidence."
</P>
<P>
The ongoing action by NATO "is not the language of peace,
cooperation, stability and prosperity in the region," he said.
"This is the language of instability and inviting trouble in the
region," long considered "the powder keg of Europe."
</P>
<P>
The white book, compiled during the NATO aggression, is the
first volume which contains information and evidence about crimes
committed by NATO and its member states against Yugoslavia from
March 24 and April 24.
</P>
<P>
"The book No. 2 is to be published soon," Jovanovic said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led NATO began air strikes on Yugoslavia, a sovereign
member of the U.N. family, without the authorisation of the U.N.
Security Council, which has the primary responsibility for the
maintenance of international peace and security.
</P>
<P>
NATO staged "anti-Yugoslavia propaganda campaign in order to
cover up their crimes against sovereign population" in Yugoslavia,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"The aggression itself, representing the crime against peace,
is the first and greatest crime," he said, "The crime of genocide,
crimes against humanity and war crimes were also committed."
</P>
<P>
NATO launched 25,200 sorties of war planes over the territory
of whole Yugoslavia, dropping 25,000 tons of explosives, he said.
"Altogether, 1,100 war planes and other most sophisticated
weaponry have been busy against Yugoslavia for nearly two months."
</P>
<P>
"NATO was unselective about its victims. Children, women and
the elderly perished, as well as mothers with their newborn
babies, patients on dialysis, refugee columns, journalists and TV
crews on assignments, farmers in the fields, vendors on produce
markets, passengers in buses and trains, people crossing bridges,"
said the book, which contains informative photos and figures on
NATO crimes.
</P>
<P>
"Among the killed civilians, 30 percent are children, while the
share of children among the wounded is even higher -- 40 percent,"
said the white book.
</P>
<P>
"The NATO military aggression is not the eye-to-eye encounter,
and there was an action by the most advanced weaponry and the
inhumane weapons," including radioactive weapons and cluster
bombs.
</P>
<P>
The NATO aggression is a war "between the invisible side in the
air and the helpless side on the ground," he said, referring to
the air attacks by advanced U.S. war planes from a very big
distance from the targets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
