<HEADLINE> AIDS Infections Grow in Eastern Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- AIDS infections in
Eastern Europe rose nine-fold in just 3 years from less than
30,000 HIV cases in 1995 to some 270,000 by December 1998, a U.N.
agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine has been the most dramatically affected and infections
in Belarus, Moldova, Kazakhstan and Russia have also grown, said
United Nations Program on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS) in a press release
issued at the U.N. headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
The agency said approximately 80 percent of infections are in
individuals who inject drugs.
</P>
<P>
UNAIDS calls for greater participation of people living with or
affected by HIV/AIDS in AIDS prevention programs due to their
unique contribution to the cause. 
</P>
</TEXT>
