<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Calls on KFOR to Honor U.N. Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The whole situation in
Kosovo, the Yugoslav province, "is very far from being
satisfactory" because the international peacekeepers, known as
KFOR, and the U.N. mission (UNMIK) "haven't implemented the
provisions (in the U.N. resolution) that related to themselves," a
senior Yugoslav diplomat said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Vladislav Jovanovic, charge d'affaires of the Yugoslav Mission
to the United Nations, told a press conference here that
disarmament of the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) "is very slow."
</P>
<P>
"There should be no vacuum gap in security in Kosovo" after the
withdrawal of Yugoslav security forces under a military technical
agreement signed between Belgrade and NATO in June, he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, KFOR began its deployment immediately
after Belgrade pulled its security and military forces out of the
Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, KFOR and UNMIK have implemented the provisions
(of the U.N. resolution) which related to themselves," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council adopted on June 10 a resolution,
calling for a political solution of the Kosovo crisis with the
respect for sovereignty and territorial integrity of the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav ambassador blamed KFOR for not preventing rebel
KLA from entering Kosovo from neighboring Albania, he said.
</P>
<P>
KLA, an armed rebel group campaigning for independence of
Kosovo, staged a comeback in Kosovo and seized power in some
areas.
</P>
<P>
"The disarmament of KLA has not been treated in a serious
manner from the very beginning," he said.
</P>
<P>
The situation has become a serious concern not only for
Belgrade, but also for the U.N. Secretary-General and the U.N.
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"If the situation develops in that way, the real danger is that
it can get out of control," he said. "Nobody knows where it can
lead."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the Yugoslav Mission has sent a memorandum to the
U.N. Secretary-General and the Security Council, "stating very
concretely our objections and request immediate and efficient
action by the KFOR and UNMIK," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
