<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Arafat Discuss Mideast Peace Process on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat Thursday discussed over
telephone ways of reviving the Mideast peace process, especially
the Palestinian-Israeli talks.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders reviewed the latest efforts exerted by the
Palestinians and Israel in their talks on a timetable for the
implementation of the Wye peace accord, Egypt's Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Wye Accord signed last October in Washington stipulates
that Israel must pull back from another 13.1 percent of the West
Bank in three phases and release hundreds of Palestinian political
prisoners. But Israel suspended the accord in early December only
after carrying out the first stage.
</P>
<P>
The telephone conversation was part of the continued
coordination and consultations between the two leaders, the news
agency said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with
Israel in 1979, plays a key role in mediating the peace talks
between the Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel have reached tentative agreement on
carrying out other aspects of the accord on September 1 and troops
pullback in October.
</P>
<P>
But the two sides are still at loggerheads over when the final
phase of the withdrawal should be completed. The Palestinians have
said the Wye deal should be carried out by mid-November while
Israel was offering to implement the final-phase pullback by
January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
