<HEADLINE> Arab League Satisfied with Sudanese Government's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League on Thursday
expressed satisfaction with the Sudanese government's decision on
cease-fire in all combat zones in the south.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the league hailed the decision as "a
positive response" to appeals by specialized agencies of the
United Nations for facilitating relief operations in southern
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army has been fighting
since 1983 for increased autonomy for the predominantly Christian
and animist south from the Muslim government.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have held several rounds of talks under the
auspices of the East African Inter-Governmental Authority on
Development to seek peaceful solution to the civil war. But little
progress has been made. Nearly 2 million people have died in the
war and related famine.
</P>
<P>
The 22-nation pan Arab forum said in the statement that Sudan's
decision was made in a bid to stem bloodshed and create a climate
for national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
It reiterated its stance on maintaining Sudan's territorial
integrity and warned that any attempt to disrupt security and
stability in Sudan would be targeting Arab national security.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government declared on August 5 the unilateral
cease-fire to facilitate the flow of relief aid in the south and
called on a rebel movement to reciprocate by a similar move to
help end the suffering of the people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
