<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000 GMT, Thursday total files are  0362 total characters are 00518905 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel agreed to speed up shipments of arms and
military equipment to India during the recent incidents in
Kashmir, the local daily Haaretz reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The daily said that the Indian government had asked Israel to
accelerate its arms shipments to India before the recent
developments in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Indian troops attacked a Pakistani-supported guerilla group in
Kashmir in May, and since then tensions between the two countries
have been running high, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Israel and India have maintained extensive security cooperation
in recent years. (BC-Israel-India)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Two people were killed and five others injured
Wednesday in an unprecedented armed robbery in Qom, a religious
city about 100 kilometers south of the capital Tehran.
</P>
<P>
An eyewitness said a group of armed robbers entered the city's
Mellat shopping mall at 22:45 local time (18:15 GMT) Wednesday and
then threatened shopkeepers to surrender their belongings and
money to them, the official Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
The robbery happened when the mall was almost closed and gold
sellers were busy collecting their jewels. The robbers, wearing
masks, grasped gold and 90 million rials (about 10,000
U.S. dollars) in cash from the shops, said the eyewitness.
(BC-Iran-Armed Robbery)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- No new timetable has been concluded so far for
implementing the Wye Accord, Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
Chairman Yasser Arafat said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the remarks at a joint press conference with
visiting Jordanian Prime Minister Abdel Raouf al-Rawabdeh at the
PNA headquarters in Ramallah, according to a report available here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat was quoted as saying the timetable demanded by the PNA
was the one agreed upon in the accord signed last October in
Washington. (BC-Palestine-Jordan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat Thursday discussed over telephone ways of
reviving the Mideast peace process, especially the
Palestinian-Israeli talks.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders reviewed the latest efforts exerted by the
Palestinians and Israel in their talks on a timetable for the
implementation of the Wye peace accord, Egypt's Middle East News
Agency reported. (BC-Egypt-Palestinians-Consultation)

