<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Hails Anniversary of Geneva Conventions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Union hailed on
Thursday the importance of the four Geneva Conventions concerning
human rights in armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement issued on the 50th anniversary of the
adoption of the four Geneva Conventions, the 15-nation bloc
stressed the primary importance of the conventions that have
served as the basic treaties of international humanitarian laws.
</P>
<P>
"The anniversary of the four Geneva Conventions is a time to
take stock and to promote the implementation of international
humanitarian law in all armed conflicts," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The union said that the conventions are as necessary today as
they were 50 years ago and it stressed full compliance with the
provisions of the conventions.
</P>
<P>
The EU statement described the conventions as being drawn up
solely for the protection of the individual in times of armed
conflicts and it called upon all countries that have not yet done
so to become a party of the conventions.
</P>
<P>
Though it recognized the achievements since the adoption of the
Geneva Conventions, the European Union deplored the persistent
violations of humanitarian laws during armed conflicts and said
that distinctions between combatants and civilians in today's
conflicts were often blurred and that children and other
vulnerable groups had become targets of conflicts.
</P>
<P>
"Bridging the widening gap between existing international norms
and respect for them should be the main objective and the issue
should be put more forcefully on the agenda of the international
community," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The union also praised the working of the International
Committee of the Red Cross and reaffirmed its support to the
humanitarian organization and its affiliated institutions
worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
