<HEADLINE> Saudi Prince's Bodyguard Detained in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A bodyguard of a Saudi prince was
detained Thursday in Egypt on a charge of assaulting an Egyptian
police officer, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The bodyguard, Farras Ahmad Tayyar, a Syrian national, is one
of the seven members of the entourage of Prince Turki bin Abdel
Aziz. Egypt has ordered the prince to remain in the country
pending the investigation.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Prosecutor General Maher Abdel-Wahed is investigating a
complaint by police officer Imad-Eddine Abaza that the prince's
son, two brothers-in-law, a friend and four bodyguards assaulted
him in a cafeteria of Ramsis Hilton hotel in Cairo in June. The
prince's son has not been forbidden to leave Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutor ordered that Tayyar be detained for four days
for interrogation, a source at the Interior Ministry told the news
agency.
</P>
<P>
There have been complaints against Prince Turki's family and
his bodyguards since they moved into the upper floors of the hotel
in 1983 after he fell out with his brother, King Fahd.
</P>
<P>
Former employees have accused Turki of mistreatment and
withholding pay. In 1997, one of the prince's American bodyguards
was arrested for punching two men who objected to his blocking a
Cairo street with his car. Three other bodyguards were deported
after similar complaints. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
