<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Urges Donors to Pay Special Attention to Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Thursday called on donors to make a special effort
to help the victims of conflicts and natural disasters in Africa
as the continent's needs have not been met.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued through his spokesman, Annan said the
needs "are nearing irrevocable crisis proportions".
</P>
<P>
The response to the aid requests has been poor with only 352
million U.S. dollars received by U.N. humanitarian agencies so far
this year against 796 million dollars requested, he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan said serious humanitarian needs cannot be met in
countries like Angola, Somalia, the Republic of Congo, Burundi,
Guinea Bissau, Sierra Leone, the Democratic Republic of Congo,
Ethiopia and Eritrea due to inadequate donor response.
</P>
<P>
"The latter five countries have recently taken important steps
towards establishing peace, These advances are tenuous and must be
bolstered by the provision of aid," the U.N. chief said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
