<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Hopes to Make Progress in Arms Control With Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States hopes it
can make progress on arms control talks with Russia, the White
House announced.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman David Leavy told reporters that National
Security Council Advisor Sandy Berger spoke with Russia's new
premier, Vladimir Putin over telephone for about 20 minutes
Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Berger stressed the importance of making progress on a
whole range of issues including arms control, nonproliferation and
economics," Leavy said.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin and U.S. President Bill Clinton
agreed in Cologne, Germany in June that they would give a new push
to a START III treaty.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Putin reaffirmed Russia's desire to strengthen the overall
relationship and cooperation and expressed that the new government
intends to follow the Yeltsin-Clinton agenda that was put forth in
Cologne earlier this year," Leavy added.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to the U.S. last month, Putin's predecessor,
Sergei Stepashin agreed with U.S. Vice President Al Gore that
Russia and the United States will start talks on arms control this
month.
</P>
<P>
Early this week, Yeltsin fired Stepashin and chose Putin as the
new premier and a presidential candidate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
