<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No New Timetable for Wye Accord: Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- No new timetable has been concluded
so far for implementing the Wye Accord, Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Chairman Yasser Arafat said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the remarks at a joint press conference with
visiting Jordanian Prime Minister Abdel Raouf al-Rawabdeh at the
PNA headquarters in Ramallah, according to a report available here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat was quoted as saying the timetable demanded by the PNA
was the one agreed upon in the accord signed last October in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
Under the Wye Accord, Israeli should have pulled out its troops
from another 13.1 percent of the West Bank by the end of last
January. Israel suspended the accord in early December only after
withdrawing from 2 percent of the land.
</P>
<P>
The PNA chairman also stressed the Palestinian stand on the
statehood with Jerusalem as the capital. The Palestinians
postponed a decision on the establishment of an independent state
before the May 17 Israeli general elections.
</P>
<P>
On his part, al-Rawabdeh asserted his country's support to the
Palestinian people for achieving their full rights, including an
independent state with Jerusalem as the capital. Israel has claimed
Jerusalem as its undivided and eternal capital.
</P>
<P>
Al-Rawabdeh has gone back home after a brief visit to the
Palestinian territories where he had talks with Arafat on
developments of the Mideast peace process and means to revive
it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
