<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African States Urged to Protect Children's Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A senior Ugandan women
official Thursday called on African governments to attach more
importance to children issues, especially their rights and
welfare.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Ethiopian capital Addis
Ababa, visiting Ugandan Minister for Gender, Labor and Social
Development Janat Mukwaya said that the situation of children in
the African region, especially in warring countries, are very bad.
</P>
<P>
Some countries tend to put children's issue at the back of law,
Mukwaya said, adding that "Children's issue must be handled with
delicacy."
</P>
<P>
The minster urged African countries to ratify Africa Charter on
the Rights and Welfare of the Child, a document designed to make a
framework for protection of children in the continent.
</P>
<P>
The charter was adopted by the 26th Ordinary Session of the
Assembly of Heads of State and Government of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) in Addis Ababa in July 1990.
</P>
<P>
Mukwaya is here to chair a two-day meeting of the Special
Committee on Children in Situations of Armed Conflict.
</P>
<P>
The special committee, established during the Conference on
Children in Situations of Armed Conflict held in Addis Ababa in
July 1997, consists of representatives of OAU member states,
international organizations and non-government organizations.
</P>
<P>
During its 3rd meeting beginning Wednesday, the special
committee focused on ratification of the Africa Charter on the
Rights and Welfare of the Child by member states and its coming
into force.
</P>
<P>
The committee noted that out of the minimum 15 ratifications
required to bring the charter into force, 13 ratifications have
been deposited at the OAU headquarters.
</P>
<P>
It hoped that the additional ratification will be deposited in
the very near future. It appeals to all African states which have
not done so to ratify the charter and bring it into force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
