<HEADLINE> U.N. Agency Reveals Growing Child Mortality in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Child Mortality in
heavily populated parts of Iraq has grown over twice since 1991,
after the United Nations imposed sanctions on Iraq, the U.N.
Children's Fund (UNICEF) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
During the nine-year period, under-five mortality more than
doubled from 56 deaths per 1000 live births to 131 deaths per 1000
live births in south and central Iraq where 85 percent of the
country's population live, the agency said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The findings in the first UNICEF survey in Iraq reveal an
ongoing humanitarian emergency, UNICEF Executive Director Carol
Bellamy said.
</P>
<P>
"Whenever sanctions are imposed they should be designed and
implemented in such a way as to avoid a negative impact on
children," she pointed out.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF called on the international community to provide
additional funding for humanitarian efforts in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
