<HEADLINE> Italy Warns KLA to Halt Anti-Serb Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini warned Kosovo Liberation Army's (KLA) guerrillas Thursday to
stop the violence against the province's remaining Serbs.
</P>
<P>
Dini denounced the KLA's failure to lay down its weapons
according to the agreed timetable and a general failure by Kosovo
Albanians to cooperate with attempts to foster co-existence
between Serbs and Albanians, Italian news agency Ansa reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He spoke of his "deep concern over the failure of Kosovo
Albanians to comply with the international community's requests,
as well as over the ongoing incidents against the Serb population
and the continuing exodus of Serbs from Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
"If violence attributable to the KLA and/or deviant groups
should continue, the international community will be forced to
reconsider reconstruction aid for Kosovo," he added.
</P>
<P>
Dini's warning came a day after UNHCR, the United Nations'
refugee agency, declared that worsening violence against Serb
residents of the Kosovo capital Pristina had reduced their numbers
from 20,000 to less than 2,000.
</P>
<P>
Two women, aged 70 and 79, were shot in their homes on Monday
night as part of a growing tide of violence aimed at driving the
last Serbs out of the ethnically Albanian province, UNHCR said.
</P>
<P>
Last week the Kosovo international peace-keeping force (KFOR)
reported nine murders and seven serious attacks in Pristina.
</P>
<P>
The situation required KFOR to intervene "with greater vigor"
to prevent violence against Serbs, Dini said.
</P>
<P>
He reminded the KLA, which some say has lost control of fringe
sections, that a United Nations Security Council resolution called
for a multi-ethnic Kosovo with broad autonomy from Belgrade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
