<HEADLINE> HK Electric Reports 1.5 Pct Profit Increase in Half Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Electric Holding
Limited announced Thursday that its unaudited consolidated profits
amounted to 1,937 million HK dollars (251 million U.S. dollars) in
the first half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the 1,909 million HK dollars (244.7 million U.S.
dollars) profit of the corresponding period of last year, the
figure represents an increase of 1.5 percent, according to the
1999 interim report of the group.
</P>
<P>
"In spite of the relatively cooler weather experienced in May
and June 1999, the overall level of sales during the first half of
1999 is in line with the group's expectations," said George C.
Magnus, chairman of the group.
</P>
<P>
The group also witnessed a slight increase in turnover to 4,038
million HK dollars (517.7 million U.S. dollars) from 4,034 million
HK dollars (517.2 million U.S. dollars) in the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the profit increase to the group's continuous
efforts on cost control and on providing reliable, environmentally
friendly electricity and excellent customer service.
</P>
<P>
All pledged service standards were either achieved or surpassed
during the period, and the high standard of environmental
protection continues to be improved, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
