<HEADLINE> Signing of SADC Trade Protocol Slow: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A Zimbabwean minister said
Thursday he is concerned at the slow pace by which member states
are moving to ratify the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) Trade Protocol.
</P>
<P>
"We are waiting for a third of the member states to ratify the
protocol in Maputo next week at the SADC summit," Industry and
Commerce Minister Nathan Shamuyarira said.
</P>
<P>
He said if the protocol was ratified it would come into
existence next January.
</P>
<P>
The protocol was critical for the region as it would see the
movement of goods in the region.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Shamuyarira said there were plans by
South Africa, Mozambique and Zimbabwe for a joint project to build
a steel mill in the Beira corridor.
</P>
<P>
The project was aimed at supplying the South East Asian region
with steel products in the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
"The plans are still at their infancy for us to make a full
statement," Shamuyarira said.
</P>
<P>
"There has been a general agreement that we should produce for
this market," he said, adding the estimated cost of the project
was 850 million Zimbabwean dollars (22.3 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
