<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Nears Final Arms Deal With Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government will consider final decisions on a 30-billion-rand
(five billion U.S. dollars) arms deal with foreign suppliers
within two to three weeks, a defense official has said.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet would make final decisions on the deals that have
been initiated with individual providers based on whether it can
afford the purchases, said Chippy Shaikh, chief of acquisitions at
the Defense Department.
</P>
<P>
The proposed purchases provided for offset investments, or
industrial participation, of about 110 billion rand (18.3 billion
dollars) in South African industry.
</P>
<P>
"We're still busy with" the affordability investigation,
Associated Press (AP) Thursday quoted Shaikh as saying. "You can
give me the best offset program and the best price structure, but
the issue of affordability is something different."
</P>
<P>
Last year, the government gave preliminary approval to a
defense package that included 28 Gripen jet fighters from
Saab/British Aerospace of Sweden and England -- the most
expensive item estimated to cost 10.9 billion rand (1.8 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The proposed deal also included the purchase of three
submarines and four corvette warships from Germany, 40 light
utility helicopters from Italy and 24 Hawk-100 jet trainers from
British Aerospace.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's chief arms negotiator Jayendra Naidoo Thursday
denied a report that the Gripen fighters deal has been closed.
</P>
<P>
"It's complete nonsense, even the amount involved is completely
wrong," Naidoo said.
</P>
<P>
The report which said Sweden and Britain had sold 28 Gripen
fighters to South Africa for 3.6 billion dollars, originated from
an unnamed Swedish radio station Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
