<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Denies Animosity Against S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Angola, with an eye on the
position of the Executive Secretary of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC), rejected the existence of any
animosity between Angola and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Every country has its own points of view on determined
questions," said Angolan Foreign Minister Joao Miranda, "so we
cannot expect that Angola and South Africa have always the same
points of view on international or regional issues."
</P>
<P>
He added that due to different internal and international
problems they face, it is "normal" that there exist "divergences"
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Miranda told the Angolan Public Television that "South Africa
is of great potential in the future of the continent."
</P>
<P>
He also said that during the fights for liberation from the
Apartheid, SADC member countries have established fraternal
relations, without mentioning a recent accusation against South
Africa by the Angolan defense minister.
</P>
<P>
On July 30, Angolan Defense Minister Kundy Payama accused South
Africa of measuring forces with Angola and regarding Luanda as a
main rival in its fight for the leadership in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Having an eye to the post of the Executive Secretary of the
SADC, Angola tried to improve its relations with SADC member
countries, especially with South Africa, which is taking the
rotating three-year presidency of the summit of SADC.
</P>
<P>
The Executive Secretary of SADC will be appointed at the SADC
summit according to the recommendation of SADC's Council of
Ministers, which is holding a meeting in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Miranda said that during the summit, which is set to be held in
 Mozambique next Wednesday, Angola will try to obtain the post of
the Executive Secretary, saying that "the candidate in favor of
Angola has been launched and we will defend it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
