<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African FM Optimistic About Congo Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- South African Foreign
Minister Nkosazana Zuma, returning from a trip to the war-torn
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), said Thursday that she was
optimistic about finding a final solution to the conflicts there.
</P>
<P>
"Every war must end. I'm still positive that a solution will be
found. It is up to all of us, especially the Congolese, to find
one," she told reporters at Waterkloof air base outside Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
But she acknowledged that her trip did not yield any
conclusion, saying that it would be premature to predict the
DPA339HAB233I12TEQL01:0301:032731
outcome of efforts to determine who was the legitimate leader of
the Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD), the main rebel group in
the Congo.
</P>
<P>
The two-day visit produced much information about a rebel
leadership dispute in the Congo, she said.
</P>
<P>
"We collected a lot of information and documentation... and
will look at that. It would be premature at this stage to make
any predictions," she said.
</P>
<P>
The dispute over the RCD leadership is at the center of a delay
in putting into action a peace accord concluded last month between
the main players in the Congo conflict.
</P>
<P>
Opposing factions in the rebel group are at odds over who
should sign the agreement on behalf of the RCD.
</P>
<P>
Ousted RCD leader Ernest Wamba dia Wamba insists this is his
prerogative.
</P>
<P>
But his Rwanda-backed rivals, led by Emile Illunga, say that
Wamba has no troops or political following. They accuse him of
being a mere puppet of the Ugandans who support him.
</P>
<P>
Zuma left Tuesday for the northeastern town of Kisangani in
Congo which has been split in two by the fighting RCD factions.
She was accompanied by the legal adviser to President Thabo Mbeki,
Mojankunyane Gumbi, and state security officials.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said her delegation, along with Zambian Minister for
Presidential Affairs Eric Silwamba, met both RCD groups.
</P>
<P>
"Our main mandate was to verify who is their real leader who
should sign. We listened to both sides and collected a lot of
documentation from them," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Together with the Zambian minister who is leading the process,
we will produce some kind of report and present it to the heads of
state."
</P>
<P>
Her visit to the Congo came after a meeting in Pretoria Sunday
between Mbeki and Presidents Pasteur Bizimungu of Rwanda, Yoweri
Museveni of Uganda and Benjamin Mkapa of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Both the Rwandan and Ugandan heads of state, who had been
backing rebels fighting to topple Congolese President Laurent
Kabila, endorsed last month' s peace accord.
</P>
<P>
The agreement calls for a cease-fire, the creation of a united
army after a 90-day dialog on the Congo's political future, and
for international peace-keepers to monitor compliance.
</P>
<P>
It was also signed by Kabila and his military allies,
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, Namibian President Sam Nujoma
and the Angolan defense minister.
</P>
<P>
Zuma could not say when a report on the rebel leadership
dispute would be handed to the heads of state concerned,
explaining this was up to the Zambians leading the verification
process.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said that the weekend fighting in Kisangani between the
RCD factions had subsided by the time she arrived.
</P>
<P>
She declined to convey any impressions on who was in control of
 Kisangani, saying: "I have my own ideas, but I don't think I want
to share them right now."
</P>
<P>
Asked about the likelihood of a reconciliation between the two
RCD factions, she said only time would tell.
</P>
<P>
"We will have to see what happens when the report is ready. I
don't think this is a matter that could be dealt with purely at a
technical level. You still have to deal with the reality."
</P>
<P>
Zuma expressed optimism that the Congo peace accord would get
off the ground. 
</P>
</TEXT>
