<HEADLINE> Egyptian-Saudi Joint Committee to Meet in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Saudi Arabia will hold
the ninth session of their joint committee in October to seek ways
for further cooperation in political, economic and cultural
fields, an Egyptian diplomatic source said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will examine the necessary steps to enhance
economic relationship and bilateral trade, including the
establishment of a joint free trade zone, Egypt's Middle East News
Agency reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is the largest Arab investor in Egypt. It has
invested 2.94 billion U.S. dollars in Egypt so far in areas
including tourism, real estate, industry and agriculture, which
accounts for 40 percent of the total Arab investments.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade reached 933.33 million dollars in 1997, with
Egypt having 115.73 million dollars in surplus. The two sides
initialed an agreement in November, which calls for setting up a
free trade zone by 2004.
</P>
<P>
The joint committee will also discuss the latest developments
in the Middle East peace process and regional and international
situation, and ways of pursuing Arab joint actions, the source
said.
</P>
<P>
The joint committee will convene in Cairo in the second half of
October under Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa and his Saudi
counterpart Saud al-Faisal.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Saudi Arabia enjoy good political relations and
maintain regular coordination and consultations on key issues in
the Gulf region, the Arab world and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The eighth session of the Egyptian-Saudi Joint Committee was
convened in Riyadh on June 22 last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
