<HEADLINE> Agro Export Earnings Fall in Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Sugar, cotton and rubber
export earnings estimatedly fell 6 percent or 4.6 billion U.S.
dollars in developing countries in 1998, according to a Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) report Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Changes in weather and economic conditions contributed to the
fall, said FAO in its 1998-1999 commodity Market Review.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations agency found that food import bills of the
least developed and net food importing developing countries rose
in the mid-1990s due partly to the generally higher prices for
cereals and to lower volumes of food aid and subsidized exports.
</P>
<P>
FAO found little evidence of any significant change in world
price instability, either year-to-year or within year, following
the conclusion of the Uruguay Round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
