<HEADLINE> Kosovo Refugees May Stay in Britain With Friends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Home Office Thursday
allowed the single largest group of illegal immigrants caught in
the country to stay with friends and relatives while their cases
are processed.
</P>
<P>
The Home Office, or the interior ministry, said it believed the
117 people claiming to be Kosovo Albanians had arrived in
southeast England in a lorry.
</P>
<P>
But they were rounded up by police on early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Members of the group, including 36 children, have been
finger-printed and photographed by officials, said a Home office
spokesman who refused to say whether the refugees were seeking
political asylum.
</P>
<P>
Authorities in Kent, southern England, said all of those caught
had left the temporary accommodation offered to them as most of
them had relatives or other close contacts in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Britain took in hundreds of Kosovo refugees during NATO's air
war against Yugoslavia. Many of them have started to return to
their homeland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
