<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Companies Recruit Directors From Outside Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Companies have increasingly
been recruiting directors from their base countries, indicating
the globalization of corporate boards, the Conference Board, a
U.S. prominent research group, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board said in a 16-nation report that the
percentage of companies with "non-national" directors increased
from 39 percent in 1995 to 60 percent in 1998. The 16 nations
surveyed are Argentina, Australia, Brazil, Canada, Chile, France,
Germany, Japan, South Korea, Mexico, Singapore, South Africa,
Spain, Sweden, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
</P>
<P>
"High level of cross-border direct investment and the
accelerating trend to raise capital from foreign investors have
forced companies to disclose vastly improved financial and
corporate information, open their communications, and redefine
their corporate culture, role and structure," said the report
authors, Lucy Alexander, a London-based research associate in the
Conference Borad's Global Corporate Governance Research Center,
and Sigrid Esser, associate director of the center.
</P>
<P>
The report said company boards are adding "non-national"
members to help gain credibility in new market and "non-nationals"
add specific expertise to help deal with the opportunities and
risks of untried market. Other factors in recruiting non-national
directors, particularly in Latin America where corporate
governance is in more of a developmental stage, include helping to
professionalize the board by providing a global, independent
focus, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the globalizing boards to changes in the
business environment, changes in the business culture and
increases in cross-border long-term investment. Cross-border M&AMP;A
transactions increased from 85 billion U.S. dollars in 1991 to 342
billion dollars in 1997, accounting for 58 percent of total
foreign direct investment flows, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report also said about 14 percent of total pro-tax profits
of U.S. corporations is generated by direct investments abroad.
From 1994 to 1997, the stock of U.S. direct investment abroad
increased by 40 percent to 350 billion dollars, amounting to 4.7
percent of the U.S. gross domestic product, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
