<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Only Gets Less Than Half Needed Aid, U.N. Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Thursday issued an urgent appeal for more aid for Africa, saying
that the gap exceeds more than 50 percent of needed aid.
</P>
<P>
Sergio Vieira de Mello, U.N. undersecretary-general for
humanitarian affairs, told a press conference here, "As of July 1,
the shortfall for humanitarian appeals in Africa was over 50
percent of what had been appealed for from donors," he said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 14.5 million U.S. dollars needed for the Republic of
Congo, also involved in a civil war, not a single dollar had been
received.
</P>
<P>
Only 352 million U.S. dollars had so far been received out of
795 million U.S. dollars needed this year to assist more than 12
million needy people on the African continent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Because of the shortfall in contributions from traditional
donor countries, "humanitarian programs have had to be cut back
and even life-saving assistance in many instances is not being
provided where it is urgently required," U.N. spokesman Fred
Eckhard said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Among the countries where urgent needs could not be met, the
spokesman listed Angola, Somalia, the Republic of Congo, the
Democratic Republic of Congo, Burundi, Guinea-Bissau, Sierra
Leone, Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
Supplies were simply insufficient to assist 2 million people in
Angola affected by fighting between the government and the rebel
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general did say 200 people are dying daily
nationwide" in Angola, de Mello said, referring to the fact that
fighting has made it hard for humanitarian aid to reach needy
people in the central African country.
</P>
<P>
In southern and central Somalia, at least 1 million people were
threatened with famine as a result of persistent conflict, six
consecutive poor harvests and grim prospects for the latest one.
</P>
<P>
"In the developed world, many countries are experiencing
unprecedented economic growth and robust budget surpluses. Yet
international aid budgets continue to stagnate or decline," said
the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Secretary-General was "alarmed by the poor response of
the international community" and contrasted this with what it
called unprecedented economic growth and robust budget surpluses
in many developed nations, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general appeals to donors to make a special
effort now to help the victims of conflicts and natural disasters
in Africa," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
