<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says India, Pakistan Ignore its Appeal for Restraint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States Thursday
expressed disappointment over the ignorance by India and Pakistan
of the U.S. appeal to abide by a 1991 agreement designed to avert
military clashes between them.
</P>
<P>
"We have been talking to them about it, and urging that they do
so," State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters at a
briefing. "I don't have any confirmation that both parties have
indicated that they will do so."
</P>
<P>
The 1991 agreement forbids aircraft from flying within about 10
km of the Indian-Pakistani border without advance notice. It also
calls for a prompt investigation in the event of a violation and
use of telephone hot lines during emergencies.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department Wednesday called upon the two
countries to abide by the agreement and urged both parties to
restrain themselves and resolve differences through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The tension has been growing in the subcontinent since India
shot down a Pakistani plane near the border Tuesday. Pakistan
accused India of "cold-blooded murder" while India alleged the
plane was shot down because it invaded its airspace.
</P>
<P>
The downing of the plane led to Pakistani troops firing a
surface-to-air missile Wednesday at an Indian military jet along
the countries' disputed border. Pakistani officials said the
Indian jets had invaded its airspace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
