<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls For Using Cleaner Fuel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
called here Thursday for research and development of biomass
technology to convert plants and trees into fuel so as to address
global warming in next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Clinton issued an executive order establishing a council to
coordinate the federal government's effort to develop a biomass
research program, and setting a goal of tripling use of
bioenergy and bioproducts by 2010.
</P>
<P>
It was possible to use bioenergy to help U.S. to meet economic
challenges, maintain security, sustain prosperity and ease the
threat of global warming, the president said.
</P>
<P>
During his visit today to the Agriculture Department, The
president will also appeal to Congress to approve 242 million U.S.
dollars in his fiscal 2000 budget proposal for research and tax
credits to promote energy efficiency, bioenergy and other clean
energies.
</P>
<P>
The White House said the ultimate goal of Clinton's order was
to replace coal, oil, natural gas and uranium with cleaner,
renewable biomass energy. If the goal was met by 2010, annual
greenhouse gas emissions would drop by more than 100 million
tons, the equivalent of taking 70 million automobiles off the
nation's roads.
</P>
<P>
If the goal was met it would also generate 15 billion U.S
dollars to 20 billion U.S dollars in income for farmers and rural
areas, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
Biomass technology uses trees, crops and waste from
agriculture or forestry to make energy that can then be used as
fuel for cars or power factories. It also can be used to create
a variety of chemicals and products from pharmaceuticals to
glue, paint or even textiles.
</P>
<P>
The executive order asks the secretaries of Agriculture and
Energy and the Administrator of of the Environmental Protection
Agency to prepare a report within 120 days on options for
increasing biomass energy use.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
