<HEADLINE> U.S. Warns Indonesian Officials Against "Intimidation" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright Thursday described as "intimidation"
Indonesia's prediction of violence on the day when residents of
East Timor vote for independence.
</P>
<P>
"This is intimidation, or worse. It is unacceptable," Albright
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
She was warning "Indonesian officials and anti-independence
militia leaders who have suggested in recent days that a vote for
independence will result in extensive violence or even civil war."
</P>
<P>
She urged all parties concerned "to ensure a fair vote and to
preserve the credibility of Indonesia's own transition, that
Jakarta meet its obligation to provide a secure environment and
promote the disarmament of all paramilitary forces in East Timor."
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said Albright was
reminding "all concerned, in the strongest possible terms, that
they are obligated to respect the results of the referendum and
provide genuine security for all East Timorese."
</P>
<P>
The East Timorese will vote for independence or autonomy on
August 30. As the day for referendum is drawing nearer, conflicts
between the anti-independence militias and pro-independence
guerrillas are increasing, leading to killings of dozens of people
there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
