<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Hopes Israel to Carry Out Wye Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said Thursday that Israel and the Palestinians
should carry out the commitments they made in the Wye River
agreement last October.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said at a briefing that
Albright was answering a message from Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak who said disputes between the two sides were a haggling that
could only waste time.
</P>
<P>
Barak sent the message through the visiting Israeli Justice
Minister Yossi Beilin. He said precious time would be spent better
by opening negotiations on a final settlement.
</P>
<P>
But Albright told Beilin that the Israeli side should carry out
its commitment to transfer another 11 percent of the West Bank to
the Palestinian Authority under the Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
This could be done while also accelerating talks on an overall
settlement, Albright told Beilin, according to Rubin.
</P>
<P>
Albright also told the justice minister that the Clinton
administration would have no problem with "modest adjustments" in
the time frame for the Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank,
Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Israel has implemented the first stage of the Wye River
agreement by relinquishing 2 percent of the West Bank. The
remaining of the 11 percent should be carried out in the second
and third stages. But it was suspended by former Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu late last year.
</P>
<P>
Barak, after assuming office, has pledged to carry out the rest
of the pullback, but he hoped the implementation of the Wye
agreement would be combined with the final status negotiations,
which was rejected by the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
Barak later agreed to carry out the accord by withdrawing the
Israeli troops at the beginning of October and completed the
pullback until next year. The Palestinians grumbled about the
stretched out schedule.
</P>
<P>
Albright is likely to work on the timetable for the pullback
and also help set a date for negotiations on final status
negotiations when she makes a trip to the region due to begin on
September 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
