<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irvine Warns Ferrari Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Eddie Irvine has said he will
leave the Ferrari team next season unless he and Michael
Schumacher are treated as equals.
</P>
<P>
With Schumacher injured, the 33-year-old Ulsterman has revelled
in his new status as number one driver with Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
He has won the last two Grand Prix to put him eight points
clear of the reigning champion, Mika Hakkinen, with six races to
go.
</P>
<P>
Schumacher broke his leg in the British Grand Prix at
Silverstone last month.
</P>
<P>
When he was asked by an Italian magazine if he was staying with
Ferrari, Irvine answered:
</P>
<P>
"That depends. If Schumacher does not return as number one, I
will stay.
</P>
<P>
"If on his return, he is again first driver, I will leave."
</P>
<P>
Irvine paid tribute to his German team-mate, declaring that he
was a faster driver: "In identical cars nobody can beat him."
</P>
<P>
But he added: "He makes too many mistakes. He has to stop
making errors."
</P>
<P>
Irvine is looking for his third win in a row in the Hungarian
Grand Prix on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The pressure is building up as he attempts to secure Ferrari's
first championship since Jody Scheckter 20 years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
