<HEADLINE> Cuba's Sotomayor Ruled out of World Championships Roster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Cuban sports officials have kept
high jumper Javier Sotomayor, who tested positive for cocaine
earlier in the Pan American Games, from competing in the world
championships to be held in Seville, not for the doping cases, but
for an injury.
</P>
<P>
"We are not going to let him compete in Seville, we are going
to keep studying him ... He needs an operation," Dr. Rodrigo
Alvarez Cambras, the head of Cuba's medical team in Winnipeg,
Canada, said on state television late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Alvarez said Sotomayor suffered a back injury at the recent Pan
American Games in Winnipeg and had later been found to be also
suffering from a hernia.
</P>
<P>
Sotomayor had his four Pan Am gold medal stripped after the
positive doping test. He has denied taking drugs, claiming he was
the victim of a set-up.
</P>
<P>
In Moscow, Russian athletics chief Valentin Balakhnichyov
called Thursday on the International Amateur Athletic Federation
to ban Cuba's high jump world record holder.
</P>
<P>
The IAAF said they had no immediate plans to suspend Sotomayor
and first wanted the Cuban federation to make a decision on the
athlete. 
</P>
</TEXT>
