<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, August 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations Thursday issued an urgent
appeal for more aid for Africa, saying that the gap exceeds more
than 50 percent of needed aid.
</P>
<P>
Sergio Vieira de Mello, U.N. undersecretary-general for
humanitarian affairs, told a press conference here, "As of July 1,
the shortfall for humanitarian appeals in Africa was over 50
percent of what had been appealed for from donors," he said. (UN-
Africa-Aid
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- Kenya has reopened its border with Somalia because
calm has returned on the other side of the border, a local source
said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The border closed early July on the heels of an incident where
a band of Somali militiamen attacked a Kenya army platoon in the
border area in North Eastern Province and snatched two army
lorries, firearms and radio equipment, which were later returned
to the Kenya army.  (Kenya-Somalia-Border)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States Thursday expressed
disappointment over the ignorance by India and Pakistan of the U.S.
appeal to abide by a 1991 agreement designed to avert military
clashes between them.
</P>
<P>
"We have been talking to them about it, and urging that they do
so," State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters at a
briefing. "I don't have any confirmation that both parties have
indicated that they will do so." (US-S.Asia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
Thursday described as "intimidation" Indonesia's prediction of
violence on the day when residents of East Timor vote for
independence.
</P>
<P>
"This is intimidation, or worse. It is unacceptable," Albright
said in a statement.  (US-ETimor)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said
Thursday that Israel and the Palestinians should carry out the
commitments they made in the Wye River agreement last October.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said at a briefing that
Albright was answering a message from Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak who said disputes between the two sides were a haggling that
could only waste time. (US-Mideast-Barak)
</P>
<P>
