<HEADLINE> Girl, Police Agents Injured in Brazilian School Shoot-out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAO PAULO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A 10-year-old girl and two
policewomen were injured here Thursday when two men shot at a
school gate from their car in the latest wave of school violence
that authorities said links to drug traffickers, the local press
reported.
</P>
<P>
The shoot-out occurred at the gate of Ministro Salgado school
in Brazil's largest city of Sao Paulo, just at midday when
students were leaving for lunch break.
</P>
<P>
Violence has long been a headache in Sao Paulo schools, where
nine students have been killed in armed clashes since January.
Reports of students being used by gangs to sell drugs in schools
have prompted authorities to impose police presence at school
gates, especially during the times of entry and exit.
</P>
<P>
According to witnesses, the two policewomen stationed at
Ministro Salgado school were watching children filing out when two
men driving by suddenly opened fire on them.
</P>
<P>
One girl student and the policewomen sustained injuries and
were rushed to a nearby hospital. Hospital sources said they were
out of danger. 
</P>
</TEXT>
