<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Japanese Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Japanese newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
Asahi, Yomiuri, Mainichi, Nihon Keizai:
</P>
<P>
-- A bill to revise the resident registration law so that a 10-
digit identification number will be assigned to Japanese nationals
was passed at a plenary session of the House of Councilors on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Asahi, Nihon Keizai:
</P>
<P>
-- After overnight confusion and a tug-of-war between Japan's
ruling and opposition parties, the Japanese parliament on Thursday
enacted a set of three anti-crime bills, one of which would allow
wiretapping during investigations into organized crime.
</P>
<P>
Asahi, Yomiuri, Mainichi:
</P>
<P>
-- The number of Japan's primary and middle school students who
missed school for more than 30 days in fiscal 1998 increased to
127,694, a rise of more than 20 percent from the previous year, a
survey showed.
</P>
<P>
Asahi, Yomiuri, Nihon Keizai:
</P>
<P>
-- In a last-ditch effort to keep their coalition intact,
senior leaders from Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party and
its coalition partner Liberal Party will endeavor to reach a
consensus on a bill to reduce the number of lawmakers, party
sources said Thursday. 
</P>
