<HEADLINE> Southern China Enjoying A Cool Summer For A Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, August 13 (Xinhua) -- While the Chinese in the North,
especially around the capital Beijing, have been wiping the sweat
from their brows in the sauna-like heat wave, people living
farther south have enjoyed a cool summer.
</P>
<P>
By the end of May, the weather began to turn hot in the capital
of the southeastern province Fujian, but several rainfalls that
followed soon expelled the heat. Residents still remember last
year's heatwave that came as early as April and hit a peak between
June and October, when temperatures hovered around 38 to 39
degrees Celsius.
</P>
<P>
This year's highest temperature reached 36 degree Celsius for
several days in June but by July the averaged temperature was
around 23 to 28 Celsius, as much as five degrees lower than normal.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists attribute the phenomenon to the La Nina effect
and say that Fuzhou's precipitation this summer was doubled the
normal amount while the daily amount of sunlight was only four or
five hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
