<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Smuggling Drive Helps Increase Revenues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, August 13 (Xinhua) --Customs officers at the port of
Fangcheng in China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region report that
they had a 99 percent rise in revenues from tariffs in the first
six months from last year's figure.
</P>
<P>
From January to June, Customs officers collected 60.03 million
yuan in tariffs, and 127 million yuan in taxes, 4.7 times last
year's figure and they attribute the increase to the more intense
efforts being used against smuggling since last August.
</P>
<P>
Fangcheng is on the Beibu Gulf where smuggling used to run
rampant. To control it, Customs officers have been cooperating
closely with local government departments, using a round-the-clock
system of supervision, intensifying patrol at docks, and strictly
scrutinizing customs forms.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months, they dealt with 71 cases of smuggling
of cigarettes, rubber, diesel oil, and other goods worth 5.31
million yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
