<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quake Rocks Sulawesi, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- An earthquake measuring 6.0 on
the Richter scale hit Luwuk in Indonesia's Central Sulawesi on
Thursday, but there were no immediate reports of damage or
casualties, the Indonesian Observer reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Residents in Luwuk town, about 1,675 km east of Jakarta, ran
out of their houses and remained on the streets long after the
tremor hit the area at around 13:46 p.m. local time on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
While it mainly jolted parts of Central Sulawesi, the
earthquake was also felt in Bitung on North Sulawesi and Kupang on
Timor island.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian Observer quoted seismologists as saying that the
quake was centered beneath the Maluku Sea, about 327 km east of
Palu.
</P>
<P>
Earthquakes with a magnitude of five can cause considerable
damage, while those of six can lead to severe damage.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, comprising thousands of islands which is part of the
so-called "Pacific Ring of Fire," is prone to earthquakes.
</P>
</TEXT>
