<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pre-Historic Animal Fossils Found in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
found a large number of fossils of pre-historic animals in a karst
cave near the capital of Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The cave is at the village of Majizhang to the northwest of the
city. They found fossils of tigers, leopards, and deer 15 meters
below ground near the cave entrance, which are believed to be 20,
000 years old.
</P>
<P>
They also discovered fossils of squid from about 300 million
years ago on a large stone outside the cave. And there were traces
of human activities with a thick layer of ash beneath a large rock
three meters from the cave entrance.
</P>
<P>
The area may have been a forest, they say, where many animals
found a quiet place for a graveyard where bones piled up over time
and were fossilized after millions of years. The discovery is
expected to provide valuable clues to the evolution of animals.
</P>
</TEXT>
