<HEADLINE> Taiwan Affairs Official Meets Reunification Alliance Group from Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Chen Yunlin, director of the
Taiwan Work Office of the Communist Party of China's Central
Committee, met here today with a visiting delegation from Taiwan's
Alliance for the Reunification of China.
</P>
<P>
Chen, also director of the Taiwan Affairs Office of the State
Council, said that Lee Teng-hui's "two states" remarks revealed
his political nature of undermining the "one China" principle and
attempting to separate Taiwan from China.
</P>
<P>
His remarks have resulted in the interruption of cross-straits
contacts, exchanges and dialogue, and the intensification and
retrogression of relations, he added.
</P>
<P>
More serious is the prospect that if Taiwan's separatist force'
s attempt to "amend the Constitution and laws" comes to fruition,
the reunification process will be aborted in the end, Chen
stressed.
</P>
<P>
"We fully respect and understand the Taiwan compatriots'
aspiration to become the masters of their homeland," Chen said,
adding that most Taiwanese are pursuing this goal within the
context of the peaceful reunification of China through cross-
Strait exchanges, co-operation and deeper understanding.
</P>
<P>
But Lee Teng-hui's remark went against the fundamental
interests of the Taiwan people and the will of the Chinese nation
to reunify the motherland, and is bound to fail, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that maintaining sovereignty and territorial
integrity is the sacred task of all Chinese, and the people on
both sides of the Taiwan Straits share common interests.
</P>
<P>
"We will firmly adhere to 'peaceful reunification' and `one
country, two systems' in the fight against Le Teng-hui's
separatist attempts in order to accomplish the final reunification
of the motherland," Chen said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
