<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: Safety Beefed Up in Manila After Powerful Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Manila, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Safety in the Philippine capital
of Manila has been beefed up following the powerful explosion at
the National Bureau of Investigation (NBI) complex in Manila after
midnight Thursday, which killed seven people and injured scores.
</P>
<P>
The blast, which was centered in the NBI's Special
Investigation Division office, sparked a two-hour fire. Several
firearms and ammunition as well as office equipment and documents
were damaged by the explosion.
</P>
<P>
The Western Police District has mounted a thorough
investigation of the explosion and those who were wounded in the
explosion have been interviewed.
</P>
<P>
NBI Director Federico Opinion said the explosion could be
targeted at SID chief Ruel Lazala, who headed a team which had
conducted a big drug operation recently.
</P>
<P>
However, there was no official report yet on what type of
device exploded in the SID office.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado declined to comment on the
NBI explosion, saying he would rather wait for the result of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Deputy Director General Edmundo Larroza of
the Philippine National Police (PNP) said the police were looking
from three angles in the explosion.
</P>
<P>
But Larroza refused to elaborate saying it might jeopardize the
 ongoing investigation. He said authorities would like to know the
real motive of the early dawn bombing.
</P>
<P>
The PNP is helping the NBI to find a clue as to who are the
people behind the bombing. Additional bomb experts have been sent
to assist the NBI and the Western Police District in identifying
the suspects as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the headquarters of the Armed Forces of the
Philippines (AFP) has declared a "red alert" state in the wake of
the deadly bomb explosion.
</P>
<P>
Brigadier General Alberto Braganza, commander of the AFP
headquarters, said the "heightened alert" is part of the security
precaution because "we cannot take chances."
</P>
<P>
According to Braganza, a program dubbed "Operation Hawk Eye"
has been fully enforced in Camp Aguinaldo, the nerve center of the
military operation, on a daily basis to prevent the entry of
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
Braganza ordered the doubling of armed guards posted in
strategic points inside the camp, especially in the evening.
Motorized armed sentinels also roamed around the military complex.
</P>
<P>
Civilians entering Camp Aguinaldo were checked to ensure that
they were not bringing in guns and explosives. Vehicles were
likewise subject to a thorough check.
</P>
<P>
Senator Rene Cayetano, also chairman of the Senate Committee on
Justice and Human Rights, urged the Senate to inquire into the
devastating explosion.
</P>
<P>
Cayetano also urged NBI Director Opinion to immediately
investigate into the incident and determine the persons
responsible for the explosion.
</P>
<P>
"The NBI should be the last edifice to be victimized by this
alarming incident," he noted. "We have to ensure that this will
never happen again."
</P>
<P>
"The safety and security of public institution as well as
private establishments should be one of our pressing concerns," he
stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
