<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK Blames U.S. for Stalemate in Four-party Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) on Thursday blamed the United States for
a deadlock in the latest round of four-party talks on Korean
Peninsula issues, saying the U.S. intentionally made use of the
four-way talks to suffocate the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
"On the sixth round of four-way talks held in Geneva, no
progress was made because of the unreasonable attitude of the U.S.,
" a DPRK foreign ministry spokesman told the Korean Central News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
"The recent and previous rounds of talks convinced us that the
U.S. is not willing to preserve peace and security on the Korean
peninsula," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The facts made it clear that the conditions are still not ripe
for a thorough discussion on Korean peninsula peace between the U.
S. and the DPRK, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Our side proposed discussing the U.S. troop pullout from South
Korea and the conclusion of a peace agreement between the U.S. and
the DPRK. ...The U.S. side, however, paid a deaf ear to our fair
and above-board demand and pursued sinister purposes," the
spokesman said, criticizing the U.S. for insisting on its previous
positions, which it has held ever since the first session of talks.
</P>
<P>
The only reason for the DPRK to attend all the preliminary and
formal rounds of talks is not to let any peace chance pass, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no change in our principled position to achieve peace
and security on the Korean peninsula through dialogue and
negotiation," the spokesman pointed out, adding that whenever and
wherever the U.S. want to sit down to discuss the withdrawal of 37,
000 U.S. troops from South Korea and the conclusion of a peace
treaty with Pyongyang, the DPRK will "make a positive response".
</P>
<P>
The future of four-way talks rests entirely with the U.S., the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The five-day sixth round of talks involving the DPRK, South
Korea, China and the United States, closed Monday with a joint
statement which said only that the next round should be held "as
quickly as possible." Five previous sessions made little headway.
</P>
</TEXT>
