<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Develop Waste-to-Energy Incineration Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government is
planning to develop two state-of-the-art Waste-to-Energy
Incineration Facilities to handle its municipal solid waste
disposal problem.
</P>
<P>
With an estimated cost of 10 billion HK dollars (1.28 billion U.
S. dollars), the facilities are expected to handle 6,000 tons
solid waste every day, said a spokesman for the Planning,
Environment and Lands Bureau Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Due to the imminent landfill shortage problem, incineration
has been proposed as the major solid waste treatment technology to
extend our landfill life and reduce the demand of future landfill
space," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Modern incineration can reduce the volume of non-recyclable
waste before landfilling by some 85 percent, render the refuse
inert and allow recovery of energy from refuse for community
consumption," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said a feasibility study is being conducted, and the study
addresses the engineering feasibility, environmental acceptability,
health impacts, contract arrangement, site selection, preliminary
design and cost estimates.
</P>
<P>
"The study is expected to be completed later this year.
Suitable sites for the development of incinerators have not yet
been decided," the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
