<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Major Power Supplier Reports Turnover Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 13 (Xinhua) -- China Light and Power (CLP)
Holdings Limited, one of Hong Kong's two power firms, Friday
reported a year-on-year increase of 1.9 percent in turnover for
the nine months ending June 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
The company's turnover reached 16.480 billion HK dollars (2.140
billion U.S. dollars) for the nine-month period, compared with 16.
173 billion HK dollars (2.073 billion U.S. dollars) in the same
period the previous year, according to an interim report issued by
CLP.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the same period of 1998, CLP's electric sales to
Kowloon and the New Territories went up 1.3 percent to 17,094
million kwh to Kowloon and the New Territories of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
If sales to the Chinese mainland were included, the total sales
rose 1.4 percent, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
CLP said sales to the domestic and manufacturing markets
decreased by 0.6 percent and 10.7 percent respectively due to the
economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the opening of the new airport and its railway in
July last year, sales to the government and other sector increased
by 8.6 percent, and sales to commercial sector rose 3.4 percent,
CLP said.
</P>
<P>
CLP Holdings Limited is the largest investor-owned electric
utility business in Asia outside of Japan.
</P>
<P>
CLP Power, the group's principal subsidiary, supplies
electricity to 1.8 million business and residential accounts in
Kowloon, the New Territories and most of the outlying islands of
Hong Kong, an area of more than 5 million inhabitants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
