<HEADLINE> Western Digital to Cut 2,500 Workers in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Disk drive maker Western
Digital (WD), a transnational company in Singapore, embarked on a
retrenchment exercise Friday to cut 2,500 jobs at Chai Chee plant
in Singapore in its operation restructuring.
</P>
<P>
The company laid off the first group of 325 workers, of which
slightly less than half are local workers, and the next group will
be retrenched in October.
</P>
<P>
Local media quoted WD's Vice President of Asian Operations John
Coyne as saying that the company is moving some operations to
Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, and the Singapore plant will focus on
product design and making high-end disk drives.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Ministry of Manpower confirmed that WD has informed
the ministry that they will realigning their hard drive
manufacturing activities and the realignment will result in
reduction of approximately 2,500 WD workers.
</P>
<P>
The ministry, together with its partners and WD, has
co-organized several re-employment and re-training events for the
affected workers and invited six electronics companies to
participate in the outplacement job fair held Friday on WD's
premises.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to the retrenchment, Singapore's National Trades Union
Congress (NTUC) said WD has treated its workers fairly in its
retrenchment package.
</P>
<P>
NTUC Deputy Secretary-General Heng Chee How said that the
lay-offs reflected the fierce global competition and price erosion
faced by disk drive makers.
</P>
<P>
It is also a reminder that the economic recovery is still
fraught with uncertainty, Heng added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
