<HEADLINE> Russia Intensifies Operation Against Rebels in Daghestan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Russia brought in more troops and
hardware to its southern Daghestan republic Friday for intensified
operations against Islamic militants controlling several villages
near the breakaway Chechen republic.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, acting Prime Minister Vladimir Putin indicated that
the campaign might be carried into Chechnya, the strongest-ever
indication that operation in Daghestan could lead to a wider war.
</P>
<P>
Five airplanes arrived in the Daghestani capital of Makhachkala
Friday carrying troops, weapons and medical equipment. Russian
defense officials gave no further details about the shipment.
</P>
<P>
While meeting with regional officials in Tomsk, Siberia, Putin
said federal authorities would pound rebel positions wherever
possible, including inside Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
"Chechnya - this is the territory of Russia, and we will strike
at militants wherever they are located," Putin said.
</P>
<P>
He said a major offensive to drive out the rebels had begun,
and the Defense Ministry said it was working to fortify strategic
facilities in the region, including a mountain tunnel that was
seized Thursday night, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Also on Friday, Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev ordered a pay
rise to Russian fighters in Dagestan, ranging from 70 percent to
170 percent depending on the nature of their mission, Tass
reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the Defense Ministry, air force planes have flown
over 200 sorties in missions against the rebels in the first day
of the operation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Interior Ministry said Thursday that 150 rebels
had been killed and 300 wounded as federal troops destroyed two
rebel bases, four anti-aircraft guns and two trucks with militants
inside.
</P>
<P>
The regional press center in the Daghestani capital said Friday
that six rebels were captured, including Shamil Ashikov, the
interpreter of Khottab, who was believed one of the two
masterminds of rebel infiltration into Daghestan.
</P>
<P>
Ashikov told interrogators that the majority of the guerrilla
force is made up of Chechens with some Arabs and residents from
Daghestan.
</P>
<P>
The rebels acknowledged losses for the first time Thursday, but
said only five of their fighters had been killed and 15 wounded,
the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Russian authorities said they have lost three helicopters
and 10 soldiers in the operation and 27 soldiers have been wounded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
