<HEADLINE> Russia Denies Delivering Air Defense Systems to Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Foreign Ministry on
Friday dismissed as speculation British press reports that Russia
shipped Yugoslavia components for S-300 air defense systems before
the beginning of the NATO air campaign.
</P>
<P>
"Russia did not send any weapons or their components to
Yugoslavia," the Interfax news agency quoted the ministry as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"Russia strictly observed and continues to observe the embargo
on arms deliveries to Yugoslavia imposed by pertinent U.N.
Security Council resolutions," it said.
</P>
<P>
"The speculations in the British press are meant only to
justify the serious violations of the corresponding U.N. Security
Council resolutions that had the purpose of the large-scale arming
of the so-called Kosovo Liberation Army, which in the long run led
to the failure of the negotiations for a settlement in the area,"
the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Jane's Defense Weekly, quoting Serbian sources, reported that S-
300 components were smuggled into Yugoslavia -- along with a
humanitarian convoy -- allegedly hidden in fuel tanks. The
beginning of the NATO air attacks, on March 24, prevented the
delivery of the remaining S-300 components, the Weekly said.
</P>
<P>
Jane's claimed that the components had been hidden in an
underground tunnel on the outskirts of Belgrade, the Yugoslav
capital, Interfax reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
