<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Leaders Welcome Back Table Tennis Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIDAIHE, Hebei Province, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese
leaders welcomed back their table tennis delegation on Friday in a
meeting here after the paddlers swept all the gold and silver
medals in the 45th World Table Tennis Championships in Eindhoven,
the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by Li Ruihuan and Li Lanqing, members
of the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the Chinese
Communist Party Central Committee, and Wang Zhongyu, State
Councilor and Secretary-General of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Li Ruihuan, Chairman of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference who also serves as honorary chairman of
the Chinese Table Tennis Association, extended congratulations and
thanks to the Chinese players for their steady great successes in
the international competitions.
</P>
<P>
It's not an easy thing to keep leading the table tennis world
with consecutive triumphes, said the Chinese leader, urging the
Chinese table tennis delegation to find out the truth behind their
success as it will most suitably serve as a good example for the
blossom of other sports in the world.
</P>
<P>
Li Lanqing, also Vice Premier, hailed the Chinese players for
another miracle in the table tennis history as they overcame the
inconvience of the shift of the venue and the postponement of the
competitions to repeat the feats achieved by their predecessors
who swept all the gold medals in both the 36th and 43rd World
Championships in 1981 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
The strong sense of great patriotism, the scientific approach
in hard training, the unremitting efforts for further improvement
after successes, are the keys for the long-time prosperity of the
Chinese table tennis in the world, said the Chinese Vice Premier.
</P>
<P>
Li Lanqing also urged the Chinese paddlers to make further
contribution to the development of the Chinese table tennis and to
the peace and friendship in the world.
</P>
<P>
Also attended the meeting were men's singles world champion Liu
Guoliang, and the doubles and mixed champions Kong Linhui, Li Ju,
Ma Lin and Zhang Yingying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
