<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CIBC Estate Biggest Sale in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian Imperial Bank of
Commerce (CIBC) is selling its entire real-estate portfolio in the
biggest deal of the kind in the country's history.
</P>
<P>
A total of 45 office, retail, industrial and development
properties across Canada will be put on sale between October 1999
and April 2000, Canadian newspapers said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Although CIBC refused to put a price tag on this deal, industry
insiders pegged the value at 1.3 billion to over 2 billion
Canadian dollars (about 0.88 to 1.35 billion U.S. dollars),
according to the newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The "crown jewel" of this package is reported to be Toronto's
Commerce Court, which boasts the prime location at Bay and King
streets.
</P>
<P>
The two-million-square-foot complex, including CIBC's head
office, is valued at between 6 million to 8 million Canadian
dollars (about 4.05 to 7.69 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
CIBC's real estate sale is "the last of Canada's big banks to
get out of the commercial real-estate business," the newspapers
said.
</P>
<P>
Royal Bank and Canada made a similar move in May when it placed
"for sale" signs on 33 properties. The Scotiabank has also put its
remaining real-estate assets on the market while other banks
dumped their holdings years ago, the newspapers added.
</P>
<P>
The spate of sales is prompted by the rebounding of the
commercial real-estate market, which endured the recession of the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
"Most of them are now going to get out of it without losing any
money," a Toronto real-estate firm director was quoted as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
