<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Forbids Redundant Industrial, Commercial Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The State Economic and Trade
Commission (SETC) today issued a directive detailing specific
industrial and commercial investment areas where redundant
construction will be banned as of September 1.
</P>
<P>
The commission urged localities not to launch any projects that
involve an apparent overproduction in such sectors.
</P>
<P>
The directive is an important industrial policy statement aimed
at prohibiting redundant construction, speeding up industrial
restructuring and reorganization, guiding investment and lifting
State-owned enterprises out of difficulties within three years,
said Zhang Zhigang, deputy minister in charge of the SETC.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of banned projects in the directive involve 17
sectors, including 201 items such as iron, nonferrous metals, coal
and gold mining, and the petrochemicals industry. These industries
are all characterized by overproduction, technological
backwardness, environmental pollution and waste of resources.
</P>
<P>
The document is subject to revision and adjustments according
to market changes and industrial development, the official said,
adding that the commission is working on a new policy to encourage
investments.
</P>
<P>
Redundant construction is a headache in China's economic
activities, and serious problems arising from low-level duplicated
construction have become outstanding as market competition heats
up, leading to serious stockpiling of products, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
A survey by the National Bureau of Statistics showed that only
a third of China's industrial sectors utilize more than 80 percent
of their productive forces.
</P>
<P>
The SETC forbids government departments and banks at all levels
approving investment projects and loans in fixed assets covered in
the directive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawian MPs Gun for More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Malawian Parliament Tuesday
passed the 1999/2000 budget estimates after a six-hour marathon
debate during which some members gunned for an increase to the
money allocated for parliament expenditure, the Malawian News
Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The MPs adopted their votes in this years expenditure on
recurrent and development accounts estimates which totalled 22,923
million kwacha or 916. 92 million U.S. dollars despite complaints.
</P>
<P>
The main controversy arose over votes concerning the committee
of supply of parliament. MPs said the 126,369,000 kwacha (505,476
U. S. dollars) given to the national assembly was below last
year's allocation although the numbers in the house have increased
to 193 from 177.
</P>
<P>
Rumphi east MP Gowa Nyasulu asked Finance Minister Cassim
Chilumpha to reconsider the vote since the house was autonomous
and not controlled by the executive.
</P>
<P>
In reply, Chilumpha said he saw no problems with Nyasulu's
proposal, noting that depending on necessity a supplementary
budget will deal with such matters.
</P>
<P>
"We can only deal with this in form of revised and
supplementary estimates," he explained.
</P>
<P>
He said as a member of parliament, he understood the problem,
but as finance minister, he did not want to blow the budget and
prevent government from reducing inflation.
</P>
<P>
Hetherwick Ntaba, lilongwe southeast MP, described the national
assembly allocation as "unrealistic," noting that there were two
revisions on the house's expenditure last year although parliament
was given 159 million kwacha (6.36 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
"With 193 MPs and escalating prices, there is no way the figure
can be at 126 million kwacha. Could the minister not take into
account?" he queried.
</P>
<P>
But Karonga northwest MP Green Mwamondwe asked the minister why
he could not allow the national assembly to adjust the budget when
ministries do so.
</P>
<P>
"Ministries blow the budget, why can't we also blow the budget
when we are the ones enacting the laws and spend time in
parliament approving these allocations?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
Chilumpha assured the members that their contributions were
valid because now the treasury would know what the house wants. He
said he was equally anxious to see that the house committees were
functional and the only way forward was for members to pass the
vote and not to delay it.
</P>
<P>
The vote was therefore passed like many other votes in this
year's expenditure on recurrent and development accounts estimates
which totalled 22,923 million kwacha (916.92 million U. S.
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
