<HEADLINE> France to Send Military Officers to U.N. Mission in Great Lakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- France will send five military
officers to the United Nations peacekeeping mission in the Great
Lakes region in central Africa, the French Foreign Ministry
announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council voted on August 6 to deploy the first
group of 90 military observers for the cease-fire in the
Democratic Republic of Congo and other countries involved in the
regional conflict.
</P>
<P>
"We intend to confirm our support of the peace process --
engaged thanks to the Lusaka agreement -- the implementation of
which is crucial for regional stability," said Foreign Ministry
Assistant Spokesman Francois Rivasseau.
</P>
<P>
The countries involved in the conflict in the Great Lakes
region -- the Democratic Republic of Congo, Rwanda, Uganda,
Zimbabwe, Chad and Angola -- signed the cease-fire agreement on
July 10 in Lusaka, Zambia.
</P>
<P>
France called on all the countries involved to make efforts for
the success of peace, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"It is important that the cease-fire should be effective in the
field and that the rebel movement of Congolese Rally for Democracy,
the only one which has not signed the agreement, do it as soon as
possible," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
