<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Land Mines in S. Somalia Kill 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Driving in Southern Somalia is
 dangerous especially around the war ravaged areas of Bay, Bakol
and Lower Jubba regions. Besides bloody ambushes by armed
militiamen, the land mines planted there claim human lives daily
there.
</P>
<P>
At least 28 people were killed and more than two others were
wounded when a Toyota pick up vehicle they were travelling in hit
a land mine Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to VHF field radio reports, the vehicle transporting
more than 35 passengers and their goods just left the town of Bur
Hakaba, about 180 Kms South of the capital at 9:00 am local time
Friday morning on its way to Bur Eylo village, about 40 Kms
further North of Bur Hakaba town when it hit the land mine.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of people have rushed to the scene of the explosion just
after the loud blast of the anti-tank land mine burst out. The
people of Bur Eylo village were the first to reach the land mine
victims since the explosion took place just outside their village.
One of the eyewitnesses whom this reporter contacted on the VHF
radio said that the vehicle was turned to rubble while the land
mine amputated limbs of human beings, making the whole place
become a shambles.
</P>
<P>
No one claimed the responsibility of the land mine. However
both Bur Hakaba and Bur Eylo towns are run by the militiamen of
the Rahanwein Resistance Army (RRA)  fighting against the
forces of faction leader Hussein Mohamed Aidid. Nonetheless, a RRA
spokesman charged that Rahanwein elements loyal to Hussein Aidid
had planted the land mine in their efforts to destabilize the
region.
</P>
<P>
This land mine is just part of major fields of land mines
planted during the fighting for control of Bay region early in the
year. Both warring sides are known to have been undergoing such
activities in their attempts of strengthening their grip on the
pieces of land they controlled. The straight tarmac road between
Mogadishu and Baidoa remains closed following the fall of the
town into the hands of the RRA in early June this year.
</P>
<P>
The other roads closed for threats of land mines are beyond the
count, especially in the remote villages of Bay, Bakol and Lower
Jubba regions. The land mine plantation campaign is further
continuing to come closer and closer to the capital as the war
between the opposing factions continues. The last such incident
was a battle wagon belonging to Hussein Aidid's men which was
destroyed by a land mine just outside Aw-dhegleh town, about 80
Kms South of Mogadishu, early in August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
