<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia Enjoys Real Peace, Stability: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Cambodia Minister for
Commerce Cham Prasidh said here Friday that his country has
enjoyed real stability and peace since the general elections in
July 1998 but everything still has to start from scratch.
</P>
<P>
He made the point in an address to a seminar hosted by the
Singapore Chinese Chamber of Commerce and Industry (SCCCI).
</P>
<P>
Prasidh said two decades of internal conflicts have reduced
Cambodia into one of the least-developed countries and now peace
is prevailing in all parts of the country while security is
largely improving.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the current situation is conducive to
the development of a market-oriented type of economy and the
economy-oriented royal government of Cambodia has taken steps in
implementing economic and political reforms to change the domestic
environment while trying to catch up with a changing world.
</P>
<P>
He also emphasized that Cambodia needs external assistance for
rehabilitation and for the development of its shattered economy.
</P>
<P>
Prasidh said his country will pursue the "Asian way" or the
"ASEAN way" towards sustainable economic growth which is adapted
to the Khmer context and follow recommendations to build an
export-oriented economy, to base development on foreign direct
investment rather than governmental or multilateral aid, and to
turn Cambodia into Southeast Asia's granary and a pivotal place
for the transit of goods.
</P>
<P>
He also said neighboring countries' success and failure need to
be learned but a success story in one country is not necessarily
another one in Cambodia and the particularities of the Cambodian
context should always be taken into consideration.
</P>
<P>
Before Prasidh's speech, SCCCI President Tay Beng Chuan made an
address to welcome Prasidh who is here on a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Due to some important policy directives announced by Cambodian
Prime Minister Hun Sen for broad fiscal reform, less spending on
defense and security, and tough action against corruption, illegal
logging and crime as well as Cambodia's entry into ASEAN and the
regaining of its seat at the United Nations, Tay said Cambodia's
current improved political stability and better economic
performance is bound to attract more trade and investments into
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Tay noted that 1998 saw a growth rate of 1 percent in
Cambodia's gross domestic product (GDP) and its improving economy
is anticipated to achieve a GDP growth of 4 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
On economic relations between Singapore and Cambodia, Tay said
Singapore's bilateral trade with Cambodia amounted to 595 million
Singapore dollars (355 million U.S. dollars), representing 0.75
percent of Singapore's total trade with ASEAN, and statistics
reveal that Singapore's imports from Cambodia, especially
garments, have registered very buoyant growth in 1998, up 49.3
percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Singapore also has investments amounting to 200 million U.S.
dollars in Cambodia and has managed to emerge as the fourth
largest foreign investor in Cambodia, Tay added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
