<HEADLINE> Turkey, Iran Sign Memo on Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Iran Friday signed a
memorandum of understanding here at the end of the sixth meeting
of the Turkish-Iranian Higher Commission on Security in a bid to
combat terrorism and safeguard border security.
</P>
<P>
Under the memo, the two countries decided to set up a telephone
and fax line to enhance cooperation between the Turkish and
Iranian commanders concerned to fight against Turkey's outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
The commanders of the two countries will plan and coordinate
operations aimed at rendering  terrorist groups ineffective and
will exchange information on border security.
</P>
<P>
Unexpected controls can be made over the desired region with a
helicopter or any convenient vehicle against a terrorist group
upon the request of a commander, said the document.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the memo also covered the bombing
allegations of the Iranian side in the Piransehir region and the
Turkish side wanted the issue to be taken up again soon after its
delegation conducts a technical observation.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has given a 50-page dossier to the Iranian side which
detailed the activities of the PKK.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Daily News reported on Monday that there are
currently about 50 PKK camps in Iran, in which 1,200 PKK rebels
are being trained every year.
</P>
<P>
These PKK militants are being brought to the Turkish border by
military planes belonging to Iran, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Ties between Iran and Turkey were strained when Iran claimed
that Turkish warplanes hit an Iranian military post and tents
belonging to Iranian tribesmen on July 18.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the bombardment had killed five people
and injured 10 others in the Iranian territory.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting since 1984 a war for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey. Conflicts between the
Turkish security forces and the PKK rebels have claimed over
37,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
