<HEADLINE> First Half CPI Inches Down in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Data released by Singapore
Department of Statistics Friday show that the Consumer Price Index
(CPI) for the first half of 1999 continued to inch down
year-on-year for households in different income groups.
</P>
<P>
The department said the CPI for all households, which declined
by 1.2 percent during the second half of 1998, continued its
downward trend falling by 0.3 percent year-on-year in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the first half of 1998, the CPI for the 20
percent lowest and 60 percent middle income groups rose by 0.9
percent and 0.1 percent respectively, it said.
</P>
<P>
Households in the 20 percent top income group, however,
experienced a negative inflation rate of 1.2 percent due mainly to
lower car prices and cheaper accommodation, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
