<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV/AIDS Program Need Commitment: WHO Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The success of the HIV/AIDS
programs depends on the commitment of all sectors coupled with
favorable policies as the Ugandan experience has shown, Regional
Director for Africa of the World Health Organization (WHO) Ebrahim
Samba said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
He said, "HIV/AIDS prevention is, and should be the concern of
all persons, from the national commitment at the highest levels to
all sectors of the society."
</P>
<P>
Addressing reporters on the 49th session of the WHO regional
committee meeting scheduled from August 30 to September 3 in
Namibia, Samba said in Uganda the rates of HIV/AIDS infection in
the urban areas had declined by about 50 percent in teenage girls
and women between 15 and 19 years.
</P>
<P>
The rate of infection among the 15 to 19 years age groups in
Uganda currently stands at six percent against the staggering high
levels recorded at the peak of the pandemic in the early 1990's.
</P>
<P>
Samba said the Ugandan success demonstrates that it was
possible to turn the tide of HIV/AIDS scourge, particularly among
the young people, thereby making it possible to save the future
generation.
</P>
<P>
He said aggressive and sustained information and educational
programs paid dividends as the Ugandan experience had also shown.
</P>
<P>
Behavioral change was more important in the fighting against
the HIV/ AIDS pandemic, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the WHO and the World Bank were in the process of
setting up a fund to assist the treatment of HIV/AIDS patients in
Africa while efforts were being made for antiviral drugs to be
sold at cheaper prices in the region.
</P>
<P>
However, he said despite the fact that out of the 33 million
Aids cases in the world 23 million cases of them were in Africa,
the continent was not getting adequate budgetary allocation to
fight the pandemic.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the 49th WHO African regional session,Samba said it
was significant in that it would determine next century's vision.
</P>
<P>
The session would discuss issues like disease control in Africa
in the 21st century, WHO's Roll Back Malaria initiative, HIV/AIDS
and other sexually transmitted diseases as well as the election of
a new regional director.
</P>
<P>
The meeting would be attended by health ministers from 46
member states of the WHO in the African region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estonia Reports High Incidence of Suicides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The suicide rate in Estonia is
two to four times higher than the world average, a sociologist
said Friday in Tallinn, capital of the Baltic state.
</P>
<P>
Ulle Suur, who heads the non-profit "Life Line" organization,
said 40 of every 100,000 Estonians take their own lives each year,
as compared to the world average of every 10 people in 100,000.
</P>
<P>
She said suicides are most frequently committed by men between
40 and 53 years old and women between 15 and 17, the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Suur attributed the suicides to depression, fatigue, loneliness,
a poor economic situation, alcoholism, drugs and gambling.
</P>
<P>
The number of suicides in Estonia peaks in late August and
early September, and again around the Christmas and New Year
holidays, she said, adding that suicides tend to be more frequent
in the spring around the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
