<HEADLINE> Japan's January-March GDP Growth Revised to 2.0 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Japan has revised upward its gross
domestic product (GDP) growth for the January-March period to 2.0
percent over the previous quarter, the Economic Planning Agency (
EPA) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The first-quarter GDP growth was initially reported as 1.9
percent growth in early June. The growth translates into an
annualized pace of 8.1 percent, revised upward from the initially
reported 7.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The first-quarter growth in GDP, the value of goods and
services minus net income from abroad, marked the first expansion
in six quarters, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
With the revision of the first-quarter GDP data, Japan's GDP
for fiscal 1998, which ended March 31, was revised to a 1.9
percent contraction from the initially reported 2.0 percent
shrinkage.
</P>
<P>
The upward revision of first-quarter GDP reflects data on
private capital spending, which was revised upward to show a 3.1
percent quarter-on-quarter increase from the initially reported 2.
5 percent growth as a result of new data from financial
institutions, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Data on exports and imports for the first quarter were also
revised, with growth in exports standing at zero against the
initially reported minus 0.3 percent, and imports at 2.8 percent
against the initially reported 1.8 percent, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
