<HEADLINE> Malawi Gives Zimbabwe Truckers cold Shoulder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Malawian transporters have
refused to accept a proposal by their Zimbabwean counterparts to
liberalize the industry so as to allow vehicles of the two
countries to carry goods as they want, the Malawi News Agency
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement from the Road Transporters
Association, the transporters' representatives refused to
liberalize the industry at the joint route management group
meeting held on July 29 in lilongwe, Malawi.
</P>
<P>
"This proposal was made with the intention of scrapping the 3rd
country rule which currently prohibits transporters of each
country from carrying goods to or from a 3rd country not part of
the agreement," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Malawians felt that the proposal would not be of any
benefit to them as there is very little use of their country's
vehicles in trade that does not have a direct relationship with
the country. It was the Malawians' belief that doing so would only
consolidate their counterpart's monopolistic situation." the
statement said. 
</P>
