<HEADLINE> Japan's Liberal Party to Remain in Coalition Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Liberal Party (LP) will
remain in the current coalition government with the Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP), LP leader Ichiro Ozawa said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Cooperation between the LDP and the LP will be maintained,"
Ozawa told a news conference after a meeting with Japanese Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi, who also serves as LDP president.
</P>
<P>
Ozawa said he and Obuchi agreed to continue debate on a bill to
cut 50 of the 200 proportional representation seats in the 500-
member House of Representatives (lower house) in the next Diet (
parliament) session, which is expected to be convened in the fall.
</P>
<P>
Ozawa had threatened to quit the two-party coalition government
unless the electoral reform bill at least cleared the lower house
by Friday, the final day of the current Diet session.
</P>
<P>
The proposed reform was part of a policy agreement reached by
the two parties before they launched the coalition government.
</P>
<P>
But the second largest opposition party, New Komeito, which is
planning to join the ruling bloc in response to an invitation by
Obuchi, is firmly opposed to the seat-reduction plan since more
than half of its lower house members were elected through
proportional representation.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the Obuchi-Ozawa meeting, the LP and New Komeito had
accepted a compromise plan presented by the LDP to carry over
debate on the bill to the next Diet session.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Ozawa also accepted Obuchi's proposal to
start policy talks among the LDP, LP and New Komeito on the
proposed three-party alliance.
</P>
<P>
The inclusion of the New Komeito in the ruling coalition would
give the bloc a majority in the House of Councilors (upper house),
which can obstruct passage of bills other than budgets and
treaties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
