<HEADLINE> Flooding Leaves 130,000 Homeless in Chad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Torrential rains striking the
central African state of Chad for the past two weeks have
destroyed 5,200 homes and left 130,000 people homeless, according
to reports Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse quoted Chad Foreign Minister Mahamat Saleh
Annadif as saying that 165,124 hectares of land have been
submerged by flood water in the Saharan desert state.
</P>
<P>
Ten of the 14 prefectures in the country and the capital
Ndjamena have been hit by the flood, and several towns in the
central, southwestern and southern regions have been submerged
after nearby rivers overflowed, said Annadif.
</P>
<P>
He called on the international community to provide food,
medicines, tents and other emergency aid to those left homeless.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains are expected to continue throughout August, said
weather forecasting service. 
</P>
