<HEADLINE> India's Congress Party Committed to Dialogue With Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 13 (Xinhua) -- India's Congress party said
Friday it is committed to a meaningful, bilateral dialogue with
Pakistan on all issues including Jammu and Kashmir, within the
framework of the 1972 Simla Agreement.
</P>
<P>
In its election manifesto released here by the party's
President Sonia Gandhi, the Congress said it wants closer
bilateral ties with Pakistan but Islamabad has to "change its
attitude to India in a most fundamental manner."
</P>
<P>
It stressed that concrete steps have to be taken to ensure that
the nuclear weapons available with India and Pakistan are never
used.
</P>
<P>
Proposals on a non-first-use pact, an agreement not to target
population centers, greater sharing of information on an advanced
warning basis needed to be studied carefully, it added.
</P>
<P>
The party also indicated that India, Pakistan and China have a
joint responsibility for nuclear non-proliferation in this region.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
