<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, U.S. to Jointly Explore Coal-Bed Methane in Jiangxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The China United Coal-Bed
Methane Corp. Ltd (CUCBM) and SABA Petroleum Inc.of the United
States signed a contract here today to jointly explore methane
resources in south China's Jiangxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Under the contract, the two partners will conduct exploration
in an area of 1,540.54 sq km at the Fengcheng Coalfield, which is
40 km from Nanchang, the provincial capital. The potential coal-
bed methane reserves in the region are estimated at 37.1 billion
cu m.
</P>
<P>
During the three-year exploration period, SABA will bear all
the expenses, estimated at 4.6 million U.S. dollars, to drill at
least 10 wildcat wells.
</P>
<P>
This contract is the sixth of its kind CUCBM has signed with a
foreign company since it was founded in 1996. According to a CUCBM
spokesman, the exploration and development of Fengcheng coal-bed
methane resources will ease the energy supply constraints in
Jiangxi, where no oil or gas deposits have been found so far. The
utilization of coal-bed methane is also expected to improve the
local energy consumption structure, which is dominated by coal at
present.
</P>
<P>
The Fengcheng Coalfield is said to have a high gas content, and
the methane resources have high permeability and lie at a moderate
depth, both circumstances favorable for industrial development.
Meanwhile, according to local officials, Fengcheng is located in
the central part of Jiangxi, where the relatively highly developed
economy and high energy consumption level add up to a promising
market.
</P>
<P>
China's total coal-bed methane resources are estimated at 35
trillion cu m, equivalent to 45 billion tons of standard coal and
equal to the country's conventional gas resources, ranking third
in the world.
</P>
<P>
CUCBM was established especially to speed up the country's coal-
bed methane development.
</P>
<P>
Companies from the United States and Australia have invested in
the exploitation of coal-bed methane in China. China has
designated coal mines in Liaoning, Anhui, and Shanxi provinces as
pilot projects for coal-bed methane development. It plans to set
up two methane production bases in north China's Shanxi Province
and build up an annual production capacity of one billion cu m by
the end of 2000. By the year 2010, the country will further boost
the capacity to 10 billion cu m.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
