<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Restraints If India Intrudes Again: Pak Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's military spokesman
Brigadier Rashid Qureshi said Friday if India attempted to intrude
again into Pakistan's airspace or territory, there would not be
much restraints exercised.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the media here, Qureshi said it depends
entirely on India to maintain restraints because it has shot down
an aircraft of the Pakistan Navy well inside Pakistan's airspace.
</P>
<P>
It can not be expected by Pakistan to exercise restraints when
an Indian fighter aircraft attempts to intrude into Pakistani
airspace while Pakistani helicopters were trying to get the
victims' bodies which were in a bad shape, said Qureshi.
</P>
<P>
He said the first Indian claim was that this aircraft was shot
down in the Indian airspace and then it glided and fell into
Pakistani territory.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that the aircraft was well about three miles inside
the Pakistani territory when it was shot at by the Indians. The
Indian air force sent a couple of their fighter aircraft as well
as some helicopters when Pakistani helicopters were picking up the
debris and the bodies of those killed.
</P>
<P>
This would be aimed, perhaps, at collecting parts of the
aircraft as they did previously and showed it on television, he
said.
</P>
<P>
To a question about the possibility of revenge by Pakistan, he
said, "That is something that the government has to decide. When
we say appropriate measures it means that we would not allow
repetition of what has happened."
</P>
<P>
"The way Indians have shot down a totally unarmed aircraft, we
will make sure that every inch of airspace and territory is
defended." he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
