<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 152 Million EU People Hold Jobs in 1998: Eurostat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A total of 152 million people
in the European Union (EU) held jobs last year, meaning an
employment rate of 61 percent for the EU work force, Eurostat
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The statistical bureau of the European community said the
jobless rate was 10.2 percent or 17.3 million people were without
a job but were available and looking for one.
</P>
<P>
Of the 125.5 million people with full-time jobs in the 15-
nation bloc, one in three were women.
</P>
<P>
Over 26.4 million or 17 percent of the 152 million people in
jobs said they worked part-time and eight out of 10 of these part-
time workers were women.
</P>
<P>
Eurostat said that Denmark had the highest employment rate of
75.3 percent, while Spain the lowest at 49.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Luxembourg had the lowest unemployment rate at 2.8 percent
whereas Spain the highest jobless rate of 18.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half the jobless people had been so for over a year.
</P>
<P>
Employees in Britain had the longest working week for those
working full-time. They worked an average of 44 hours last year,
3.5 hours more than the European Union average and 4.3 hours more
than the 11-nation Euro zone average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
