<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Congress Party Promises Stable Govt in Manifesto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 13 (Xinhua) -- India's Congress party issued
its election manifesto here Friday, pledging to provide a "stable,
able and experienced government" if it were elected in the general
elections next month.
</P>
<P>
"The most urgent need today is for a stable government, for a
government that completes its full term in office," said the
manifesto, released by Congress President Sonia Gandhi.
</P>
<P>
It accused the coalition government led by the Bharatiya Janata
Party (BJP) of failing to ensure national security and said the
18-month coalition demonstrated "unprincipled and opportunistic
politics."
</P>
<P>
The government, which collapsed last April, had spent more time
at pleasing coalition partners than with the task of governance,
the Congress said.
</P>
<P>
The manifesto promised to preserve and promote secularism,
enhance social justice and empower the weaker sections of the
society besides making the government responsible, representative
and responsive.
</P>
<P>
The 60-page manifesto also promised various measures to check
population boom, provide better education, health and housing
facilities and strengthen the public distribution system.
</P>
<P>
On economy, the Congress party pledged to accelerate economic
growth and new investments to make the country truly self-reliant
and create 10 million new jobs every year, broad-base agriculture
and promote small scale industries.
</P>
<P>
If it wins the election, the party said, it will usher in a
fiscal responsibility act to discipline government expenditure,
new companies, competition and foreign exchange, to restructure
the administered price mechanism in the oil sector to provide
subsidies for kerosene only.
</P>
<P>
It would work to create a South Asian Parliament and make South
Asia Free Trade Association in reality soon.
</P>
<P>
Saying that faster employment generation and poverty
alleviation would be the cornerstone of the party's economic
policies, the manifesto promised to speed up the implementation of
public and private infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
On relations with neighboring China, the party said
confidence-building measures would be expanded.
</P>
<P>
"While recognizing that we have border disputes with China that
need long-term negotiations in mutual good faith," the manifesto
said, the Congress would seek to build closer economic, trade,
cultural, educational and political ties with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
India, Pakistan and China have a joint responsibility for
nuclear non-proliferation in this region, said the manifesto.
</P>
<P>
The party said it would engage the United States in a
comprehensive dialogue on all issues of mutual concern and will
take concrete steps to institutionalize this dialogue.
</P>
<P>
It will also take steps to consolidate closer economic and
commercial links with the European Union and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The traditionally close relationship with Russia would be
continued and consolidated, said the Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
