<HEADLINE> Nigeria Senate May Summon Former State Head to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's former Head of State
General Abdulsalami Abubakar may be invited by the country's
Senate to explain how a debt of 250 billion naira (2.63 billion
U.S. dollars) was accumulated between December 1998 and May 29
this year, reported a Nigerian newspaper Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Senate Committee on Local and Foreign Debts,
Senator Idris Abubakar said Thursday that a motion would be
submitted to invite principal players of the former government to
give explanations on the debt, said Vanguard, a leading Nigerian
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Senator Abubakar, in making a case for the invitation of Gen.
Abubakar and his other senior aids including former Minister of
Finance and Central Bank Governor said their explanations would
be offered at a public forum to enable Nigerians to ask them
questions.
</P>
<P>
He said that his committee had stumbled on the debt while it
was going through the financial records made available to it by
the finance ministry.
</P>
<P>
"We discovered that the sum of 250 billion naira was reflected
as debt from December 1998 and May 29 and when we inquired, we
were told it was for ways and means to fund government projects,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Before the May 29 hand-over to civilian rule this year,
officials in Abubakar administration had been criticized to
engage in a spending spree to leave the following government an
empty treasury.
</P>
<P>
Some critics even accused certain officials of looting the
country's wealth before leaving office.  
</P>
</TEXT>
