<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Moves to Promote Peace, Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada has allocated a bigger budget for the promotion of peace
and order in the Philippines, Philippine News Agency (PNA)
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
In his budget message to Congress, Estrada said he has
allocated 37.5 billion pesos (937 million U.S. dollars) for the
Department of Interior and local government for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
This amount represents a 21 percent increase from the 31
billion peso (775 million dollars) budget for the same purpose for
1999, the PNA said.
</P>
<P>
According to Estrada, his administration continues to give high
priority to peace and order "to ensure the safety of our people at
home, in the streets and their work place."
</P>
<P>
Estrada also pointed out that peace and order helps create an
environment conducive to vibrant business activities and, thus,
stimulate overall economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The president said he has urged Congress to approve his
proposed 651 billion peso (16.2 billion dollars) national budget
for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Also, the Estrada administration has reportedly set aside 685
million pesos (17 million dollars) for use of the Presidential
Anti-Organized Crime Commission (PAOC) and its operating arm, the
Presidential Anti-organized Crime Task Force (PAOCTF), in the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
The PAO/PAOCTF budget, intended for operations as well as
coordination of efforts by all law enforcement agencies in peace
and order campaigns, is higher than the 1999 allocation of 518
million pesos (12.9 million dollars). 
</P>
