<HEADLINE> Pakistan Says Making Progress in Eliminating Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has made significant
progress in eliminating child labor and creating awareness among
the masses against this menace, Director Dani Appave of the
International Labor Organization (ILO) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a weekly press briefing here, Dani said that
"universal primary education and ratifying the proposal with
regard to minimum age for admission to employment are a real
breakthrough."
</P>
<P>
"There is more awareness among the masses," said Dani, adding
that he could not see any child engaged even in floor cleaning at
big industrial estates in Karachi, the southern port city.
</P>
<P>
He said that in spite of the many challenges and problems
encountered, the efforts made by the Pakistani government are
appreciable.
</P>
<P>
Dani also mentioned the efforts of the soccer ball industry in
the Punjab town of Sialkot and said they have made "tremendous
headway in the right direction."
</P>
<P>
He said the ILO with the cooperation of the Pakistani
government has finalized workers education program for the
promotion of awareness amongst workers with regard to AIDS.
</P>
<P>
He said the new manpower and labor policy announced by the
Pakistani government emphasizes the will of the government to
progress on the application of the ILO conventions ratified by
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The ILO official appreciated the constitution of a commission
on consolidation, simplification and rationalization of labor
laws. He stressed the need of full participation of all the social
partners in the commission.
</P>
<P>
Dani was of the view that Pakistan has short supply in skilled
labor. The government should do more in human resource
development, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
