<HEADLINE> Stocks Close Sharply Lower on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Share prices gyrated from
positive to negative territory on the Singapore Stock Market
Friday, closing sharply lower and offsetting Thursday's gains.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) dropped 43.13 points to
end at 1,969.68 points, the lowest level in 65 days.
</P>
<P>
The total volume was very thin, contracting to 209.01 million
shares valued at 444.12 Singapore dollars (about 264.75 million
U.S. dollars). Falls outnumbered rises by 294 to 40 with 111
counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
AFP continued to be the most active stock with a turnover of
15.06 million units. Hotung remained the second heavily traded
share with 11.60 million done. GES was the next with 9.11 million
counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
SIA topped the actives chart as it climbed by 30 cents to close
at 15.50 Singapore dollars. Creative 50 edged up 20 cents to
finish at 17.00 Singapore dollars. Acer w01 inched up 5.5 cents to
end at 0.43 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, SPH and SPH 100 led the losers of the day as
both of them lost 60 cents to close at 27.90 Singapore dollars.
IDT sank 56 cents to finish at 1.70 U.S. dollars. Bukit Sem
retreated 50 cents to end at 16.00 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that market sentiment was dampened by an
announcement that Malaysia is to be reinstated in the Morgan
Stanley Capital International Index.
</P>
<P>
They said the announcement had drawn attention away from the
Singapore market as fund managers rebalanced their portfolios in
favor of Malaysia. 
</P>
