<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China and Tajikistan Sign Joint Statement (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Tajik government reiterates its stand that the government
of the People's Republic of China is the sole legitimate
government of China and that Taiwan is an inalienable part of
Chinese territory and it opposes any attempt to create "two Chinas
" or "one China, one Taiwan" and says that it will not establish
any form of official relations and carry out any form of official
exchanges with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The two welcome the upcoming Bishkek summit of participants in
the Shanghai and Moscow pacts and believe the summit is another
common step in strengthening trust and understanding in Eurasia.
</P>
<P>
The two sides express their concern over the escalation of
armed confrontation in Afghanistan and emphasize that efforts made
by the "6+2" states are of important significance and a continuous
effort should be made to find a peaceful solution to the Afghan
conflict.
</P>
<P>
The two support observing the principles of mutual respect for
sovereignty and territorial integrity, non-interference in each
other's internal affairs, and resolving differences and disputes
through friendly consultations and oppose the random use of force
or the threat of it in international relations and support the
authoritative role of the UN in handling international and
regional affairs.
</P>
<P>
The two express a willingness to increase consultations and
cooperation in international affairs and make concerted efforts to
establish a just and fair new international political and economic
order.
</P>
<P>
President Rakhmonov extended an invitation to President Jiang
Zemin to pay an official goodwill visit to Tajikistan, the date
and schedule of which can be settled through diplomatic channels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
