<HEADLINE> Iraqi Grain Warehouses Bombed by U.S.-British </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Warplanes of the United States
and Britain have shelled grain warehouses in the southern Iraqi
province of Muthana, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
INA quoted a Trade Ministry spokesman as saying that at 19:30
(1530 GMT) Tuesday, U.S. and British warplanes bombed warehouses
of the state company of construction materials which were used by
the State Grain Board.
</P>
<P>
He said that the bombardment caused damage to the rice in the
warehouses as well as the windows, ceilings and walls of some
warehouses.
</P>
<P>
"Such cowardly acts once again reveal the falsity of
allegations of U.S. and its crony Britain that they are keen on
alleviating sufferings of the Iraqi people," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's airstrikes against Iraq, U.S. and
British warplanes have been regularly attacking Iraqi civilian
facilities and military sites in the no-fly zones, causing severe
civilian casualties and property damage.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were imposed on Iraq by the U.S.-led Western
allies following the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed aim of
protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the
south from attacks by Iraqi government troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
