<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Consumption Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- China's economy managed to stay
on a fast track as consumption improved and investment continued
to slow down in July.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released by the National Bureau of
Statistics (NBS), consumer prices in July dropped by 1.4 percent
from June, and retail prices dropped by 2.6 percent from June.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales totaled 238 billion yuan in July, increasing by 5.
6 percent over the same period of last year. The sales-production
ratio of industrial products rose to 97.4 percent in the month, 0.
6 percent higher than one year ago.
</P>
<P>
Exports increased by 7.5 percent year-on-year to 17.3 billion U.
S. dollars in July, ending a declining trend in the first half of
the year. Trade surplus was 3.4 billion U.S. dollars in July,
accounting for nearly one-third of the past seven month's total.
</P>
<P>
China's trade volume totaled 189.1 billion U.S. dollars in the
past seven months, an increase of 5.4 percent over the same period
last year, as exports totaled 100.2 billion U.S. dollars, import
88.9 billion U.S. dollars, and the trade surplus was 11.3 billion
U.S. dollars for the period.
</P>
<P>
China's industrial output and the profits of enterprises
continued to increase in July. However, investment in fixed assets
saw a 11.3 percent drop from the first half year.
</P>
<P>
Investments in fixed assets totaled 829.8 billion yuan in
January-July, up 12.7 percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
During the period, incremental value of industry reached 1101.3
billion yuan, increasing 9.4 percent year-on-year, while Chinese
industrial enterprises registered total net profits of 72.9
billion yuan in the first half of the year, an increase of 70.7
percent over the same period last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
