<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Graf Says Goodbye to Tennis due to Injuries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 13 (Xinhua) -- German tennis legend Steffi Graf
announced her retirement in her home town on Friday, ending a
career with 22 grand slam titles.
</P>
<P>
At Heidelberg, the 30-year-old former world number one veteran
said she was quitting from the sport immediately after a series of
injuries.
</P>
<P>
Graf, who won the Wimbledon titles seven times, had hoped to
play her 54th and last grand slam tournament at the U.S. Open in
September, but an injury to her left hamstring forced her to skip
the tournament in California and changed her plans.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Graf said she would stop playing major tournaments
at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Graf, the undisputed best women tennis player of her generation,
became the youngest player to receive a WTA ranking at 13 years
and four months in 1982.
</P>
<P>
She has won 107 tournaments and held the top spot for 377 weeks,
an all time record.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, the blonde won the grand slam of the four major
tournaments plus the Olympic title in Seoul. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Factfile of Steffi Graf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Following is a fact file on Steffi
Graf who announced her retirement on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Aged 30, born June 14, 1969
</P>
<P>
Birthplace: Bruehl, Germany
</P>
<P>
Lives: Heidelberg, Germany, and Boca Raton, Florida
</P>
<P>
Right-handed
</P>
<P>
Total titles: 107
</P>
<P>
Grand Slam titles: 22
</P>
<P>
Australian Open: 1988, 1989, 1990, 1994
</P>
<P>
French Open: 1987, 1988, 1993, 1995, 1996, 1999
</P>
<P>
Wimbledon: 1988, 1989, 1991, 1992, 1993, 1995, 1996
</P>
<P>
U.S. Open: 1988, 1989, 1993, 1995, 1996
</P>
<P>
Graf has dominated the women's tennis, in particular at
Wimbledon, for 15 years and has been ranked number one for a
record total of 377 weeks.
</P>
<P>
In 1982, she became the youngest player to receive a WTA
ranking at 13 years and four months.
</P>
<P>
Over the past years, she has been hampered chronic back injury
caused by bone spurs in her back and had a knee surgery in 1997.
</P>
<P>
On June 8, 1998, she was dethroned from the WTA top ranking for
the first time since 1983 as she only played two tournaments in 12
months.
</P>
<P>
Graf bounced back this year to win the French Open and reach
the Wimbledon final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
