<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Protects Forest Resources of Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Qamdo Prefecture in southwest
China's Tibet Autonomous Region will plant dragon spruce, fir, elm,
and other tree varieties in valley of the Jinsha River, a
tributary of the Yangtze River, during the next few years.
</P>
<P>
This is part of the prefecture's effort to protect the
ecological environment of the upper reaches of the country's
longest river, the Yangtze, in line with the central government's
policy.
</P>
<P>
The forests and shrubbery of the Jinsha River Valley play an
important role in protecting the ecological environment at the
source of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government began banning logging Jomda, Markam, and
Gonjo counties of the prefecture late last year in a bid to
improve the ecological environment of the region.
</P>
<P>
Qamdo and Nyingchi prefectures of Tibet reportedly will
implement an afforestation project at a cost of 300 million yuan
with the help of the State Forestry Administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
