<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Parliament to Revise Alien Registration, Immigration Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Diet (parliament) Friday
enacted two bills to revise the country's alien registration and
immigration laws, abolishing fingerprinting for foreign residents
and making illegally staying in Japan a separate punishable
offense from illegal entry.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which revises Japan's Alien Registration Law,
requires nonpermanent foreign residents aged 16 and older living
more than one year in Japan to give a signature instead of a
fingerprint, and submit information of family members when they
register at local municipal offices.
</P>
<P>
Japan's fingerprinting system has been criticized as treating
foreigners like criminals since it was introduced in 1955.
</P>
<P>
The new law is expected to affect some 630,000 foreign
residents in Japan. The existing documents containing the actual
fingerprints will be destroyed, government officials said.
</P>
<P>
Japan abolished compulsory fingerprinting for foreigners with
permanent resident status in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Another bill revises the Immigration Control and Refugees
Recognition Law to make illegally staying in Japan a punishable
offense separate from illegal entry.
</P>
<P>
Under the current law, offenders found to have illegally stayed
in Japan three years or more after illegally entering the country
can only be deported and not prosecuted for the crime of illegal
entry.
</P>
<P>
With the revision, illegally staying in Japan will become a "
continuing offense" and offenders could be sentenced to up to
three years in prison, or fined up to 300,000 yen (about 2,631 U.S.
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
