<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin not Dissolve Duma, Aide Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
will not disband the State Duma, Alexander Kotenkov, his
representative in the lower house, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
While some Duma members want the house to work peacefully until
the end of its term in December, others would like to precipitate
a political crisis, Kotenkov said following a meeting at the
Kremlin with Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the lower house will approve Yeltsin
's nominee for prime minister, Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma is scheduled to hold an extraordinary session
next Monday to debate the candidacy of Putin, who was picked up by
Yeltsin last Monday to replace Sergei Stepashin as the fifth
premier in about 18 months.
</P>
<P>
"Common sense should prevail in the Duma," the Interfax news
agency quoted Kotenkov as saying.
</P>
<P>
Most observers believe that the lower house will likely confirm
Putin in their first try Monday as most lawmakers want to leave
the latest government change behind and concentrate on the
preparations for the next parliamentary elections, scheduled for
December 19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
