<HEADLINE> Press Leaders Refute Lee Teng-hui's Separatist Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The All-China Journalists
Association called a meeting today to refute Lee Teng-hui's "two
states" remarks.
</P>
<P>
Zheng Mengxiong, vice-chairman of the association, said Lee
openly opposed the "one China" principle and tried to separate
Taiwan from China, and this act is firmly opposed by all Chinese
people, including the country's 550,000 journalists.
</P>
<P>
He said that during the past month the mass media in the
country have strenuously criticized Lee Teng-hui's separatist
nature, and have upheld the common aspirations of the Chinese
people.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that working hard to unite all the Chinese people
including Taiwan compatriots to realize the reunification of the
motherland is a noble and unshirkable duty of the Chinese mass
media.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the People's Daily, Xinhua News Agency, CCTV,
Beijing Evening News, and other media organs delivered speeches at
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
They said they believe that Lee's "two states" remarks reveal
Lee's desire to split the motherland, and that his opposition to
the "one China" principle is aimed at totally destroying the basis
for contacts, dialogue and negotiations across the Taiwan Straits,
and hindering the process of reunification.
</P>
<P>
They urged Lee to give up his "two states" remarks, adding that
otherwise Lee will be condemned by history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
