<HEADLINE> New AIDS Drug Hit Uganda Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A new AIDS drug has hit the
Uganda market, bringing the total of anti-AIDS drugs to about 25.
</P>
<P>
Known as Ziagen(abacavir), the new drug is said to be very
effective, the New Vision newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is the first African country to access the drug because
of its advanced efforts in fighting AIDS, Sales and Marketing
Regional Director Parmindar Lotay of Glaxowellcome, the
manufacturing company, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
A patient is supposed to take 300 milligrams of the white
tablet twice a day and this will cost the patient 420,000
shillings (300 U.S. dollars) a month, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The drug lowers theviral load in the blood and improves the
general health of the patient. If combined with other drugs like
AZT and 3TC, the new drug can reduce the virus in the body to
undetectable levels.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is among the first countries to have reported cases of
AIDS. The HIV prevalence rate has reduced to 12 percent among the
population from over 30 percent a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's remarkable achievements in this field have been
recognized by many international organizations and it has been
awarded several prizes for this progress.
</P>
<P>
However, most of the AIDS drugs manufactured so far are much
more than average Ugandan AIDS patients can afford. As a result,
many health institutions are still searching for an affordable
AIDS drug for common patients of the epidemic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
