<HEADLINE> Lebanon Raises Oil Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon has slapped on a slight
price hike on gasoline and other petroleum products in the light
of the sharp increase of oil prices on the international market,
the Daily Star reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Oil Minister Suleiman Traboulsi Thursday issued an
official statement announcing an increase of 20 Lebanese pounds
(0.013 U.S. dollar) per liter on prices of gasoline and other
petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
The oil prices on the international market have witnessed a
sharp hefty from 117 dollars a ton of gasoline in January to the
current 231 dollars a ton.
</P>
<P>
Liquefied gas' price has risen from 151 dollars a ton eight
months ago to 256 dollars at present while fuel oil has gone up
from 96 dollars a ton to 154 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Traboulsi promised that the ministry would reduce the oil
prices when international prices dropped.
</P>
<P>
The move quickly sparked the protest by the General Labor
Confederation, Lebanon's largest labor union grouping 350,000
workers.
</P>
<P>
The group's head Elias Abu Rizk said the government's policy
would only deepen the economic and social crisis and devastate
low-income people's living. 
</P>
</TEXT>
