<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Law Official Calls for End to Local Protectionism (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A top Chinese official in
charge of law and order urged local and departmental leaders today
to abandon protectionism and put an end to the wide-spread
practice of interfering in the enforcement of court rulings.
</P>
<P>
Luo Gan, member of the Political Bureau of the Communist
Party of China (CPC) Central Committee and state councilor, made
the appeal here today at a national tele-conference of the CPC's
Central Commission of Politics and Law. Luo also heads this
Commission.
</P>
<P>
Because of economic interests, local and departmental
protectionism has long plagued Chinese courts in the enforcement
of court orders, and has resulted in "law enforcement difficulties,
" now well-known among legal professionals.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that by the end of June this year, more than
850,000 court rulings were yet to be executed, involving over 259
billion yuan (31.2 billion US dollars). Illegal official orders
and violent activities interfering in the enforcement of court
rulings have been common an occurrence across the country.
</P>
<P>
"Solving the problem of law-enforcement is not only the
task of the people's courts," Luo said, noting that the CPC
Central Committee attaches great importance to this problem.
</P>
<P>
All the leading officials of local Party committees,
government, and cabinet branches must view the gravity of this
problem in the light of safeguarding the long-term stability of
the country, he said, stressing that "no government bodies, armed
forces, political parties, special interest organizations, or
enterprises shall be entitled to the privilege of going beyond the
limit of the law."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Law Official Calls for End to Local Protectionism (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Luo outlined several steps to be taken against interference
in the enforcement of court rulings at today's meeting:
</P>
<P>
-- Local policies and regulations running counter to the
national law and the enforcement of court orders should be
resolutely nullified soon;
</P>
<P>
-- Those illegally interfering in the enforcement of court
orders and causing severe consequences shall be investigated for
further punishment;
</P>
<P>
-- For enterprises which illegally transfer their property
in an effort to evade debts or instigate a large number of workers
to challenge and stymie the enforcement of court orders, related
Party committees and government offices should take prompt action
to punish those responsible.
</P>
<P>
-- A nationwide inspection shall be launched jointly by
local Party committees and local legislative bodies later this
year to address this issue, and the number of non-enforceable
court rulings shall be substantially reduced by the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Yang, president of the Supreme People's Court, said at
the meeting that the attention of the central authorities and
local governments will bring great support to the courts, and the
courts across the country shall do their utmost to ensure the
authority and dignity of the law.
</P>
<P>
Cao Zhi, vice-chairman of the National People's Congress (
NPC) Standing Committee, attended today's meeting, which was
heard by leading Party, people's congresses and government
officials from all provinces, autonomous regions, and
municipalities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
