<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Africa Ranked Among Top Emerging Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 13 (Xinhua) -- South Africa had arisen as
one of the most popular emerging markets in the aftermath of the
financial crises of the past two years, according to Standard &AMP;
Poor's Micropal, one of the World's leading research houses.
</P>
<P>
It said in its latest survey of 94 emerging markets that South
Africa had attracted net inflows of 175 million U.S. dollars in
the first quarter of this year, ranking the fourth.
</P>
<P>
Another Micropal survey among 32 global emerging market equity
funds showed that the trend continued into April, with South
Africa attracting more than two thirds of the $300 million
invested in African and Middle Eastern markets during the month.
</P>
<P>
The funds pumped almost 1.1 billion dollars into emerging
markets in April, a major show of confidence, considering they had
invested only 85 million dollars in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The quarterly and monthly surveys also confirmed that east
Asia, the original source of much of the emerging market crises,
was firmly back in favor. It attracted the largest flows with
about 550 million dollars during April, followed by Africa and the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Micropal said South Africa was the fourth most popular country
on an average weighted basis during that month, with the 36 funds
increasing their exposure by 2.6 percent to 7.86 percent between
March and April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Observing Ozone Layer in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-one Chinese and Japanese
scientists are in Tibet for one month to observe the ozone layer
there and carry out relevant studies.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the Institute of Atmospheric Physics under the
Chinese Academy of Sciences and Nagoya University in Japan have
already arrived in Tibet for trips to Lhasa, Xigaze, and
Yangbajain to conduct their research. They will also release a
high-altitude balloon to monitor the ozone layer above Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The scientific expedition, which is jointly sponsored by the
National Committee for Natural Science Fund and the Beijing
Greencool Environmental Production Engineering Co. Ltd. will help
promote global ozone studies and the study of biological and
environmental changes in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The latest surveys have shown that the shrinking ozone layer
has become a global environmental problem in the past decade, with
the ozone content in atmosphere reduced by three to eight percent,
and the size of the hole in the ozone layer above the South Pole
has doubled. Chinese scientists have also found a thinner ozone
layer above the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the rapid reduction of the ozone layer will
increase the incidence rate of skin cancer and cataracts, and
cause great damage to animals and crops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese News Agency Asks Why Lee Teng-hui Is Running Rampant? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Xinhua News Agency, in a
commentary today, further exposes Taiwan leader Lee Teng-hui's
true nature of indulging in separating Taiwan from the motherland
by quoting his August 10 remarks about worldwide commotion caused
by his earlier remarks on "state-to-state relations."
</P>
<P>
Lee described the confusion as "very good," saying "the worse
the results of the incident become, the better" he feels.
</P>
<P>
The commentary says that Lee's recent remarks reveal to the
world his true nature and his deliberate attempt to sabotage cross-
straits relations, but he is meeting opposition from countries
around the world and has been strongly condemned by the Chinese,
including those on Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Lee was under great pressure and had to defend himself by
arguing that he had not mentioned "two states" but said "special
state-to-state relations" instead and has claimed that he is not a
trouble-maker and that there has been no change in Taiwan's "
mainland affairs policy."
</P>
<P>
However, the article asks, because Lee wants to separate Taiwan
from China, how can these explanations disguise his wild ambition?
</P>
<P>
Over the past few days, anti-Chinese forces in the U.S. have
increased their activities, it says, with some people urging the U.
S. administration to sell more arms to Taiwan and others
advocating the drafting of a bill to strengthen the security of
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The "two states" remark is the distillation of all Lee's plots
and his backers are international anti-Chinese forces, but as long
as he continues his "two states" remarks and doesn't return to the
basic "one China" policy, the Chinese will fight him.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
