<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China and Vietnam Resuming Direct Mail Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- China and neighboring Vietnam
recently resumed the direct mail service, which was suspended for
more than 20 years, at Yunnan Province's Hekou County through
posts and telecommunications departments of Yunnan and Vietnam's
Lao Cai.
</P>
<P>
Letters and packages have had to be carried by air from
Beijing to Hanoi on twice-weekly flights before.
</P>
<P>
Hekou County and Lai Cao face each other across a 200-meter
bridge over the Nanxi River, which allows trains, vehicles, and
pedestrians to move back and forth. The town is 296 km. from Hanoi.
Each day, five passenger and cargo trains and over 50 trucks go in
and out of the border port.
</P>
<P>
Trade through the port is worth 700 million yuan a year.
</P>
<P>
Direct mail services between Pingxiang in China's Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region and Lang Son in Vietnam also resumed
recently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
