<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Use Legal Means to Punish Afghan Killers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Iran said it would use every
possible legal means to identify and punish those Taliban
militants responsible for the 1998 killing of Iranian diplomats
and reporter in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA)
Friday, Iranian Foreign Ministry's director for Afghan affairs,
Mohammad Ebrahim Taherian, said if the international community
fails to arrest and punish the "murderers," Iran would use
whatever legal tools available to punish them.
</P>
<P>
Eight Iranian diplomats and an IRNA correspondent were killed
when Taliban troops took over Mazar-i-Sharif, a stronghold of the
opposition Northern Alliance in August 1998. Iran has been
demanding identification and punishment of those responsible.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been supporting the opposition forces while Pakistan
backed the Taliban, which has won control over most of Afghanistan
in the civil war in the Middle Asian country.
</P>
<P>
Taherian said some of the killers have been identified, but he
did not mention how this was achieved.
</P>
<P>
He asked Afghan people to help Iran find and identify "all
culprits of the heinous crime."
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official also said his country is for an
independent, free, and united Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
