<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Bank Providing Settlement Services For Futures Traders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Industrial and Commercial
Bank of China (ICBC) announced today that it will provide more
services for futures traders.
</P>
<P>
A bank spokesman says that it has signed agreements with China'
s three futures exchanges in Shanghai, Zhengzhou, and Dalian to
help them handle capital settlements and will provide them and
traders with safe and fast capital settlement services nationwide
to minimize risks and ensure the healthy development of the
futures business.
</P>
<P>
Futures trading first started in new China in the early 1990s
and in 1998 the State Council issued a ruling on standardizing
markets. All of the country's 14 pilot futures exchanges were
subsequently merged into 3, and in 1998, their combined trading
volume was 3.75 trillion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman says that the bank will help the exchanges
accelerate capital turnover, strengthen capital supervision, and
improve capital operating efficiency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
