<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Marketing Institute Seeks Legal Backing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Institute of Marketing
(ZIM) is advocating for an Act of Parliament to regulate the
marketing profession in the country.
</P>
<P>
ZIM president Hapenga Kabeta said the institute had processed a
layman's draft of the Act and handed it to the Ministry of
Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
The Post, a Zambian newspaper, Friday quoted Kabeta as saying
that the law would include all marketing professionals but exclude
non professional people practising marketing.
</P>
<P>
"After the Act is passed it will become illegal for any company
to employ anyone other than marketing professionals registered
with ZIM," he said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said ZIM was advocating for the proposed Act to become law
by next year. The law would exclude non trained people from
practising marketing.
</P>
<P>
Kabeta said the marketing fraternity had not done well in
marketing Zambian products.
</P>
<P>
"Marketing has become more relevant in this liberalized economy
and the job of the marketer is to ensure their products are in the
mind of the consumers whenever they have to choose among a number
of goods," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ZIM board secretary Mapesa Musongole said Zambia
companies needed to invest more in market research in order to
know more about the markets they operated in.
</P>
<P>
He said although market research was expensive, it was
important for successful marketing.
</P>
<P>
"We also intend to introduce marketing ethics to give guidance
to all participants in the marketing sector, thereby regulating
things such as advertising and marketing consultancy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kabeta said ZIM would work on a marketing handbook for
reference purposes that would be relevant for the next century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
