<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Maize Output Down by 25% </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenya will register a 25-percent
drop in maize production this year, according to a latest report
by the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Only 1.7 million tons of maize will be harvested after this
year's long rains reason, representing a 20-percent reduction
from the 1991/1997 average output in the long rains season.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation newspaper Friday quoted the ministry as saying
that even assuming a normal 1999/2000 October--February short
rains season, Kenya will face an estimated 500,000 tons deficit
between July this year and next June.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's third downward revision of its harvest
prediction has been attributed to substantive crop losses in the
crucial growing Nakuru District in central Kenya as well as in
other important grain-producing areas.
</P>
<P>
The government, the report said, has adopted the agricultural
ministry's recommendation that 180,000 tons of maize be imported
to cover the July- November deficit.
</P>
<P>
At the end of July, the Kenyan government announced to lower
duty levied on imported maize from 32.5 percent to 25 percent to
encourage grain traders for importing maize from outside.
</P>
<P>
The report said, additional maize imports would become
necessary after April next year, regardless of the quality of the
1999/2000 short rains season.
</P>
<P>
The maize deficit are mainly caused by poor rainfall during the
1998/ 1999 short rains seasons coupled with the continued absence
of rainfall during most of this year, the report noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
