<HEADLINE> Dialogue Should Lead to Solution of Kashmir Dispute: Pak PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif Friday said that Pakistan's policy of dialogue with India
remains unchanged but said it must be meaningful, and should lead
to the resolution of the Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
In his Independence Day message, the prime minister said that
it is obvious that without the resolution of the Kashmir dispute
"our region will remain afflicted with turmoil and peace and
stability will continue to elude South Asia."
</P>
<P>
On the occasion of the Independence Day falling on August 14,
the prime minister said there have been many changes in the
political structure, the economy and the social characteristics of
Pakistan and its people during the past 52 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's WWI Veteran to Be Honored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's last surviving World
War I veteran, recognized for his service by France earlier this
year, will be awarded the rank of sub-lieutenant, the Bangkok Post
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Royal approval was being sought for the promotion of Yod
Sangrungruang, 101, who served as a private in the army during
World War I, as a token of appreciation for his devotion to the
country, the newspaper quoted Army Chief General Surayud Chulanont
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Yod enlisted in the army and volunteered in 1917 to serve as
one of the 1,284 soldiers in the Royal Siamese Expeditionary Force
to fight with the Allies in France.
</P>
<P>
In 1918, the 19-year-old Yod served as a mechanic in the French
army, based near Marseilles.
</P>
<P>
On his return to Thailand in 1919, he received a military
decoration, the Victory Medal, bestowed by then King Rama VI.
</P>
<P>
After the disbanding of the expeditionary corps, he settled
down in his hometown in northern Phitsanulok province.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Yod, the only surviving member of the expeditionary
corps, was named as a good samaritan of the province.
</P>
<P>
In January this year, he was honored by the National War
Veterans Organization for his service in the army during World War
I and was awarded the Legion of Honor, chevalier grade, by France.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras, Rafter, Kafelnikov Reach ATP Quarter-finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- American Pete Sampras
celebrated his 28th birthday today and his wealth of experience
showed in his performance at the $2.2 million ATP Championship in
Cincinnati, the United States.
</P>
<P>
The top seed and last year's runner-up, Sampras extended his
winning streak to 19 matches with a hard-fought 7-5, 7-6 (7-2)
third-round victory over Germany's Rainer Schuttler.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Patrick Rafter of Australia and Russia's
Yevgeny Kafelnikov had an easier time with their third-round
opponents. Third seed Andre Agassi had a tougher test but also
prevailed.
</P>
<P>
The second-seeded Rafter dumped No. 15 Nicolas Lapentti of
Ecuador 6-2, 6-3. Kafelnikov, seeded fourth, beat American Chris
Woodruff 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Agassi completed the quartet of top seeds in the quarter-finals
when the two-time champion got past unseeded Czech Jiri Novak 7-6
(7-3), 7-6 (7-5).
</P>
<P>
Seeking his fourth straight title, Sampras will face nemesis
Richard Krajicek of the Netherlands in the quarterfinals. A winner
of four straight matches over Sampras, the seventh-seeded Krajicek
breezed past American Justin Gimelstob 6-4, 6-2 tonight.
</P>
<P>
Fifth seed Tim Henman of Britain will face Kafelnikov in the
quarter-finals after beating No. 12 Nicolas Kiefer of Germany 6-4,
6-1.
</P>
<P>
Sixth seed Gustavo Kuerten of Brazil set up a quarter-final
showdown with Agassi by defeating No. 11 Tommy Haas of Germany 7-5,
7-5.
</P>
<P>
Also, two-time champion Michael Chang of the United States
advanced to only his third quarter-finals of the year by disposing
of Frenchman Cedric Pioline 6-1, 6-4. Chang will battle Rafter for
a semi-final berth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
