<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Export Earnings From Leather Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's export earnings from
the leather sector dropped by over 11 percent in the 1998-99
fiscal year ending on June 30 as compared with the previous fiscal
year, the Financial Express reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh earned 168.24 million U.S. dollars in 1998-99 by
exporting about 187 million square feet of leather as compared to
190.26 million dollars in the previous fiscal year, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The 1998-99 figure, which is 11.57 percent less than that for
1997-98, has fallen short of the target by 25.23 percent.
</P>
<P>
The leather sector's contribution to the country's total export
earnings, which remained static at around 6 percent over the last
few years, has also come down to 3.17 percent in 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
The main reasons behind the shortfall are a fall in prices in
the international market, stiff competition from Southeast Asian
countries and massive devaluation of their currencies in those
countries.
</P>
<P>
The total quantity of leather exported in 1998-99 was 61.24
million square feet up from the previous fiscal year, but the
value declined substantially due to a massive price fall in the
international market.
</P>
<P>
About 20 percent of the total leather export consists of
finished leather while the rest is crust being used as raw
material in importing countries.
</P>
<P>
Economic returns in terms of value addition in finished leather
production compared to crust are much higher. But the country
could not optimize its export earnings from the sector as more
than 60 percent of registered tanneries are either closed down or
inoperative due to lack of facilities required for finished
leather products.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh started exporting leather goods in 1990-91 and
earned 2.84 million U.S. dollars. After 7 years, the total
earnings from exports of leather and leather goods went up to
237.91 million dollars in 1997-98, covering 6.5 percent of the
country's total export earnings.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are over 200 tanneries employing about 65,000
people, and about 500,000 people are engaged in the leather trade.
The Bangladeshi government has already identified the sector as a
thrust of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh exports about 180 million square feet of finished
and crushed leather every year to major buyers like Italy, France,
Spain, Brazil, China and Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
