<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Say Earth Calamity Not Very Likely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The prophecies about a great
calamity for human beings in 1999 are nothing but a fallacy,
according to scientists in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Predictions about a great calamity at the end of the 20th
century at least as far back as Nostredamus in the 16th Century,
according to Li Jing, a professor at the Chinese academy of
Sciences' Beijing Astronomical Observatory. Li told a forum
sponsored by the Chinese 2000 Year Committee and the Chinese
Academy of Sciences that in his book Nostredamus predicted 1,000
major historical events by the end of the 16th Century and the
great calamity, doomsday, was one of them.
</P>
<P>
He says that a Japanese man also wrote a book in the 1970s
saying that a large "planetary cross" would appear in the sky on
August 18, 1999 and could cause the great calamity predicted by
Nostredamus. A certain planetary alignment is to appear in space
on August 18 of this year, but not in the form of a planetary
cross, Li says, explaining that gravitational forces between
planets are very weak and are not strong enough to cause any
disasters on earth.
</P>
<P>
Some astronomical events can be related to natural disasters on
earth, but they could not in any way cause any great calamities,
according to Han Yanben, of the National Astronomical
Observatories. He says in addition that scientific awareness can
help human beings improve their ability to forecast or prevent
natural disasters, and that people should not believe fallacies
that are not backed by hard scientific evidence.
</P>
<P>
Some people and organizations have used celestial phenomena to
support their fallacies, according to Ai Guoxiang, the head of the
National Astronomical Observatories, and scientists should try to
promote popular science and help people get rid of superstitious
beliefs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
