<HEADLINE> Floods Claim 114 Lives in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Floods and landslides
triggered by incessant monsoon rains have killed 114 people in
different parts of Nepal over the last two months, The Kathmandu
Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the Home Ministry as saying that 26 people are
still missing, while 3,612 families have been affected since this
year's monsoon season began on June 10.
</P>
<P>
The Home Ministry estimated the total property loss at over 156
million rupees 2.2 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
According the ministry, monsoon floods and landslides have
affected 64 of the country's 75 districts. Most of the severely
affected districts are the hilly districts.
</P>
<P>
Undersecretary of the Home Ministry Dr. Meen Bahadur Poudel
said that the government has allocated 250 million rupees (3.6
million U.S. dollars to compensate and rehabilitate the flood
victims.
</P>
<P>
Nepal's three-month long monsoon rains, which subside
completely after mid-September, claims hundreds of lives every
year. A total of 246 people were killed by floods and landslides
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
