<HEADLINE> Slum Dwellers Clash With Police in Bangladesh, 50 Injured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 13 (Xinhua) -- At least 50 people, including two
policemen, were injured and over 100 vehicles were damaged in the
Bangladeshi capital Thursday during clashes between slum dwellers
and law-enforcing members, press reports said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The slum dwellers in Mohammadpur and Tejgaon thanas
(sub-districts) in the city came to the streets Thursday morning
to block roads in protest against the eviction of slums.
</P>
<P>
Police arrested eight slum dwellers for being involved in
damaging vehicles on the streets.
</P>
<P>
Many parts of the city turned into battlefields as the
law-enforcing agency personnel and the slum dwellers clashed.
Police charged baton, used water cannon and fired teargas to
disperse the demonstrators, who attacked the police with lethal
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Dwellers of about 40 slums under Mohammadpur thana, in the
western part of Dhaka, blocked all the roads and lanes of the
locality to force the government to put an end to the eviction
program, disrupting road communications in many parts of the city
for hours.
</P>
<P>
A rumor spread Wednesday night that the law-enforcing agencies
would evict all the slums in the city on Thursday as part of the
government initiative to clear the city of slums.
</P>
<P>
There are an estimated 2 million slum dwellers in Dhaka, which
has a population of about 9 million.
</P>
<P>
The government started demolition of the city slums on Sunday
following the killing of a police constable in the city last
Friday. According to the government, the slums has become dens of
criminals who were responsible for drug and arms trafficking, and
other anti-social activities such as hijacking and toll extortion.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bangladesh's High Court on Thursday extended its
stay order till August 19 which it issued Wednesday directing the
government not to remove any more slums in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
The court passed the order Wednesday following the writ
petition filed by three non-governmental organizations and two
slum dwellers, challenging the legality and authority for
demolition of slums in the city and eviction of the inhabitants
without arranging alternative accommodation and without any prior
notice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
