<HEADLINE> Flood Evacuation Warning Issued in North Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's northern province of
Mae Hong Son issued a warning Thursday asking the province's
residents to be prepared to evacuate to high ground, The Nation
newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Heavy downpours started Wednesday night and continued till
Thursday in the province, causing flash floods in several areas
and prompting Thai Airways International to indefinitely cancel
its domestic flights.
</P>
<P>
Mae Hong Son Meteorological Office chief Pisit Pungsuwan said
the rains have measured 40.5 millimeters since Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Anan, mayor of Mae Hong Song's Muang District Municipality,
said several areas in the district had already been inundated
because of flash floods. He said the floods had damaged a bridge
on a bypass road, forcing the closure of the road.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, authorities reported from the northern province of
Nan that many roads and areas along the Nan river had been
inundated because of the swollen river following several days of
rains.
</P>
<P>
The Meteorological Department in Bangkok warned Thursday that
heavy rains would continue in several Northern provinces. 
</P>
