<HEADLINE> China Uses Seawater To Treat Waste Gas in South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, August 13 (Xinhua) -- China began yesterday using its
first waste gas treatment facility that uses technology from
Norway's electric giant ABB in Shenzhen, the first economic zone
in China.
</P>
<P>
The 200-million-yuan pollution treatment project is connected
to a 300,000 kw thermal power generator at the city's Western
Power Plant and uses seawater to eliminate sulfur dioxide from the
plant's waste gas. This helps remove 7,000 tons of pollutants
discharged by the plant annually without the use of other
chemicals and producing no residue.
</P>
<P>
The Pearl River Delta, which is near Shenzhen, has become the
victim of acid rain because of the large amount of sulfur dioxide
in the region's air. Acid rain causes several billion yuan worth
of damage to the region annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990813.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Host ASEAN NTO Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar will host the 10th
meeting of National Tourism Organizations (NTO) of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) on August 25-26,
the New Light of Myanmar newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, to be attended by representatives of ASEAN member
nations as well as those of ASEAN tourism agencies and the ASEAN
Promotion Center, is aimed at promoting cooperation among ASEAN
member nations for the development of tourism.
</P>
<P>
Along with the NTO meeting, meetings on ASEAN Communications
Team for Tourism and the ASEAN Task Force on Tourism Investment
will also be held.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN is making efforts to restore the vibrancy of the
grouping's tourism industry. At their meeting in Singapore in
January, ASEAN tourism ministers agreed to launch a Visit ASEAN
Millennium Year in 2002 in the Philippines with focus on
international travel and tourism in the region.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to promote eco-tourism and a cruise tourism
program, and to establish a network among ASEAN Tourism Training
Centers with emphasis on new job skills and new technologies in
tourism policy and planning.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, a total of 292,282 foreign
tourists visited Myanmar in fiscal 1998-99 which ended in March.
Tourists from other ASEAN member countries accounted for 5 percent
of the figure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
