<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Cabinet Endorses Joint Research With U.S. on TMD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 13 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese cabinet on Friday
endorsed a plan to start joint technical research with the United
States on a U.S.-proposed anti-missile system, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The endorsement paved the way for the two countries to sign and
exchange diplomatic notes next Monday to start the joint research
on the theater missile defense (TMD) system.
</P>
<P>
Defense officials of the two countries are expected to exchange
a memorandum of understanding to stipulate in detail how to divide
up the research work between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum will cover only the first half of the five- or
six-year period for joint research, when the two countries will
focus on designing the equipment to be used in the TMD project,
such as infrared sensors to detect enemy missiles.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will exchange another memorandum of
understanding before moving into the next stage of research to
create trial products and test them.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo and Washington agreed last December to start this year
the joint research on the TMD, which is designed to protect the U.
S. and its allies from incoming ballistic missiles flying within a
3,000-kilometer radius.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will share an expected cost of 50 billion to
60 billion yen (439 million to 526 million U.S. dollars) for the
research, with Japan shouldering between 20 billion yen (175
million dollars) and 30 billion yen (263 million dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
