<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polo: A Popular Classical Chinese Sport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
discovered a 1,000-year-old mural depicting people playing polo,
suggesting that the sport has not always been the sport of
privileged Westerners.
</P>
<P>
The mural, which was discovered in north China's Hebei province,
shows a man wearing peculiar trousers standing in front of a horse
and a child beside him holding two polo sticks.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists say that the theme of the mural is a bit unusual
but that the sport started in the 3rd century in China and became
popular among members of the imperial family. It was also used for
training in the army.
</P>
<P>
The archeologists say they believe that polo was introduced
from Central Asia into China through the Silk Road, but admit that
they don't understand why the sport lost its charm by the 17th
century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
