<HEADLINE> 100,000 to Converge in Colombo for Peace Walk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 13 (Xinhua) -- Over 100,000 representatives
from over 10,000 villages in Sri Lanka are to converge in Colombo
on August 29 to press for an early end to the civil war in the
north and east of the country.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued Friday by Dr. A.T. Ariyaratne, president of
the Sarvodaya or All People's Prosperous Movement, said that
delegates from all parts of the country will gather at a Colombo
park after a two-kilometer, meditational peace walk through
Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Religious dignitaries, political leaders, representatives of
peace organizations and voluntary organizations will join the
walk.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan President Chandrika Kumaratunga, Opposition Leader
Ranil Wickremesinghe and leaders of various other political
parties have expressed their support for the peace walk.
</P>
<P>
Religious leaders will conduct their own religious rites and
bestow blessings on the initiative. Thereafter there will be a
one-hour peace meditation.
</P>
<P>
The meditational walk and peace meditation aim to raise the
spiritual consciousness of people and thereby direct their minds
towards national unity and ending the terrors of violence and war,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has been plagued by a 16-year-old civil war fought
between security forces and Tamil rebels who demand a homeland for
minority Tamils in the north and east of the country.
</P>
<P>
Arrangements are being made to broadcast the program live over
the electronic media to enable the entire country to participate
simultaneously in the program.
</P>
<P>
The organizers hope to conduct similar programs in other towns
as well so as to cover the whole country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
