<HEADLINE> Foreigners Learning More About China Through Language Studies (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Nina, a 22-year-old graduate of
Nanjing University well remembers an encounter 6 years ago that
caused her to make a decision about her life, just after she came
to Nanjing.
</P>
<P>
She had come with her parents who are Russian and who came to
teach at the university. She couldn't speak a word of Chinese but
liked to ride around Nanjing by bus. Other passengers showed a
great deal of interest in her blonde hair but she couldn't
understand them and often got very upset. As a result, she swore
that she would learn the language and understand every word of it.
</P>
<P>
Not only did she learn to speak Chinese but she wrote a
graduate thesis on classical Chinese poetry and won the praise of
her tutors. She now want to be a teacher back home and to help the
Russians learn more about China.
</P>
<P>
Every year, about 400 foreign students come to Nanjing
University to study Chinese. The Chinese government has
established special groups for this purpose, with Chen Zhili, the
minister of education, at its head.
</P>
<P>
There is also a special Chinese language test for foreigners
and Ministry sources say that there has been a 20 percent increase
in the number of foreigners taking the test, which is referred to
as China's TOEFL. Last year, at least 40,000 foreigners took the
test and China now has test centers in 10 foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
The test has been held annually since 1990. Zhao Guocheng, the
director of the Ministry of Education's Chinese language for
Foreign Students division, says that if a foreigner passes level 3
of the 11-level exam he or she can major in science and
engineering at an average-level college without taking another
language test.
</P>
<P>
But some key universities, like Beijing and Qinghua, require
foreigners to pass the level 6 before being accepted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
