<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Criticizes Transnational Banana Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican Foreign Trade
Minister Samuel Guzowski on Thursday criticized transnational
banana firms for unilaterally cutting the price paid to national
banana producers.
</P>
<P>
The firms made the decision at the end of last month to cut the
average producer pay by 20 cents to 5.83 U.S. dollars per box of
18.14 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Guzowski said the unilateral price cut has threatened about one
third of the 170 plantations registered in Costa Rica and put them
into difficult conditions to maintain production.
</P>
<P>
Three big transnational companies -- Del Monte, Chiquita and
Standard Fruit -- control banana trade in the world. They have
their own plantations in Costa Rica, but also buy fruit from small
and medium-sized national producers, according to an official of
Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
The firms attributed their price cut to the fall in fruit
prices in the United States and to the disputes with the European
Union over exports.
</P>
<P>
Banana sector generates 170,000 jobs in Costa Rica, which is
the second banana producer in the world. Last year it exported 116
million boxes of banana worth around 664 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
