<HEADLINE> Asia's Tallest Woman Found To Have Brain Tumor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 13 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese woman whose height
of 2.33 m (7.645 feet) makes her the tallest woman in Asia and the
second-tallest in the world, is to undergo surgery to remove a
brain tumor.
</P>
<P>
Yao Defen, weighing 177 kg, has been diagnosed as suffering
from a glandular tumor in the brain due to abnormal secretion of
pituitary hormones, according to a report in the Guangzhou-based
Yangcheng Evening News.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old resident of Shucheng County, in east China's
Anhui Province, has been admitted by the Sanjiu Brain Hospital in
Guangzhou. Doctors told the newspaper that her ailment, if
untreated, could lead to cerebral edema, blindness and even death.
</P>
<P>
The hospital has prepared special-sized clothing, shoes, a bed
and a toilet for Yao, and will not charge her treatment fees "
since her illness is of great significance for medical research,"
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
