<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil to Launch Campaign Against Work-Related Accidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Brazil is launching a national
campaign against work-related accidents, chief of a national
workers' union announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This campaign, which emphasizes metallurgic and civil
construction sectors, is designed to give workers knowledge
regarding work-related accidents so that they may know how to
prevent them, said Moreira Fereira, President of Brazil's National
Confederation of Industry.
</P>
<P>
Moreira said Brazilian entrepreneurs must consider the money
used to prevent work-related accidents as investment and not cost.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 alone, work-related accidents and occupational diseases
caused a total loss of 5.8 billion U.S. dollars to Brazilian firms.
The largest number of accidents occurred among workers aged
between 20 to 29.
</P>
<P>
In the past two decades, labor accidents fell by 400 percent.
However, as many as 140,715 accidents occurred last year, in which
3,785 workers died and another 397,469 were injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
